description:
Good food,good ambience, good time!
The recipe for a Great Weekend! 
#greatweekend

I found this restaurant while looking for Nice Japanese food with Great Ambience. JYPSY at Martin Road is the concept created by the people behind PS.Cafe. With a menu of Japanese inspired delights, this restaurant is a must-try for those who enjoy a contemporary take on classic cuisine. The restaurant concept is a beautifully unique setting that takes inspiration from coastal fishing villages, blended into a contemporary chic environment. They are moving soon to new flaship at One Fullerton & their last day (23.01.2022)at 38Martin Road.

We tried the Salmon Tacos ($15), Classic Sashimi 9 pcs ($28) & Wagyu Beef Fried Rice ($26) & Nests of Fries($11) .For the drink we tried glass of Rose' Wine ($17).

Tacos is a must try, with cripsy seaweed & inside they put a lot salmon chunks with wasabi sauce on top. Squeeze a little bit of lemon & damn thats really delicious. For the sahimi, it's so so for me. Omg for Beef Fried Rice, grilled meat is juicy & with kombu butter fried japanese rice, it's the nxt lvl kind of fried rice, super tasty. For the Nests of Fries, I want to try it out cuz almost every table they ordered this. I must say that's alot of Fries & 2 person cannot finished it ğŸ˜….

ğŸ‡¸ğŸ‡¬ Calling out all coconut water lovers!  Do you like to drink coconut water? For me, I like it because coconut water is cooling, will reduce heartiness from your body and it will cure food poisoning.

I know these coconut water benefits because I experienced it before (when I stay in Jakarta). Coconut water is also good for skin. 

Speaking of coconut water, yesterday I went to NTUC FairPrice Waterway Point and found out that they currently have a promotion of buy three CocoThumb for only $5.95. Original price for each CocoThumb is $3.90. 

What a great deal, right? 

This CocoThumb appearance is unique because the coconut water is still inside the fruit. CocoThumb also contains pure coconut water from Namhom coconut tree.

So how to drink it? Do we need to open it ourself using knive? No need. By doing three step instructions from them, you can drink this coconut water: pull the red seal, push the top tube and insert the straw provided inside the tube. 

Fyi, you need to push the top tube a bit hard to make a hole on the coconut shell. 

This coconut water is refreshing. The downsides are itâ€™s a bit hard to push the top tube, this CocoThumb is very bulky & heavy to hand carried and you cannot eat the coconut flesh unless you open it yourself using knive (I would not recommend this as coconut shell is normally super hard).

Other than those downsides, this CocoThumb is a good option to satisfy your coconut water craving.

ğŸ‡¸ğŸ‡¬ I recently went to Hougang Village by taking the bus from bus interchange near Hougang MRT station.

When I got there, I passed by one hawker centre and saw super long queue line in front of noodle stall named Li Fatt Wanton Noodle.

Because of my curiosity, I decided to join the queue. 

Fyi, Li Fatt Wanton Noodle is selling five different types of noodle: Wanton Noodle, Fried Wanton Noodle, Shredded Chicken Noodle, Dumpling Noodle and Chicken Feet Noodle.

Each of the noodles types have two different prices: $3.50 and $4.50.

You can also request to add-on other toppings with additional price.

I ordered Wanton Noodle ($4.50) with additional Chicken Feet (2 pieces for $1.50) to take away.

This wanton noodle consists of noodle with charsiew, steamed wanton, green vegetables and chicken feet. Because the price is $4.50, this noodle portion is super a lot.

Wanton noodle taste is similar like the old school wanton noodle taste. Itâ€™s deliciously good.

The noodle texture and taste is nice.

The charsiew is quite a lot and tender.

Steamed wanton noodle is also delicious.

Chicken feet is quite huge and I like it. 

No wonder this wanton noodle stall has a lot of fans (based on the queue line). Li Fatt Wanton Noodle could be said as a hidden gem wanton noodle stall.

Overall I am really pleased trying this wanton noodle and I recommend you to try if you are nearby.

Itâ€™s also baked until the top of the custardâ€™s egg tart is scorched. Normally Portuguese Egg Tartâ€™s custard is creamier than Chinese Egg Tart.

I actually like both of the egg tarts version, but Portuguese Egg Tart will give you a better crunchy bite texture sensation when you chew it.

This Madeleineâ€™s Original Portuguese Egg Tart is yummy and the custard is not too sweet. The skin casing is also crunchy.

When I saw that @thebelly_eats has launched a new range of bee hoon cum noodle homemade dishes along with her popular ngoh hiang rolls, I thought â€œWow, perfect combination for a yummy meal!â€, and quickly placed my order for dinner. 

The food arrived rather early around 3ish in the afternoon, but no problem. I simply kept them in an airy spot and come evening, reheated the ngoh hiang in the toaster oven and bee hoon in the microwave and viola, dinner is ready. 

The stewed pork bee hoon was so good, loved that the rice vermicelli was so qq and fragrant with bites of stewed pork, generous amount of vegetables and umami sliced mushrooms. The crispy fried shallots and sliced chilli given by Helen added more fragrance and heat to the dish, which was seasoned just right. One box is good for 3 persons actually. 

For the ngoh hiang, itâ€™s a different take from my familyâ€™s recipe, but they were very enjoyable with the sweet and tangy belachan chilli dip. So chunky and crunchy with water chestnut bits too, 2 or 3 rolls with the bee hoon is just nice!

Simple and easy Honey Pomelo Tea èœ‚èœœæŸšå­èŒ¶, only requires 3 ingredients, a Pomelo, some rock sugar and honey.

First of all, scrub the pomelo with salt and rinse the surface with water. 

Cut the skin of the pomelo and remove the white part in between the skin and slice thinly. (the white part is very bitter) 

Separate the pulp from the white part skin of the pomelo and set aside. 

Boil pomelo peel in boiling water for 3 mins and rinse. Repeat if water still taste bitter.

Cook pulp and peel. Add rock sugar and simmer till the sauce thicken.

Wait for the pomelo sauce to cool completely and place in a 100% sanitized airtight jar.

Add honey and keep in the fridge.

[Prawn & Fish Ball Kway Teow]

One of the favourite dish that couldnâ€™t go wrong â€¦ Itâ€™s convenient & easy to cook.

Recipe:
Kway Teow (flat rice noodle)
Vegetables or bean sprouts 
Garlic, minced
Prawn
Fish ball
Eggs
Cooking oil 

Sauce:
Red chili paste (blend big red chili + garlic + small red chili + a little water)
Oysters sauce
Light soy sauce
Sweet soy sauce (kecap manis)
Few dash of pepper
*Splash a little water (last)

Method:
1. Heat cooking pan with olive oil, sauteÌ minced garlic. 
2. Stir fry prawns & fish balls until almost cooked, push aside. Add in egg, let it sit for awhile & scrambled. stir well.
3. Add in rice noodles, vegetables and chili paste, stir to combine.
4. Add in all sauce to taste. Continue to stir fry and correct taste.
5. Lastly add a splash of water. Give a final stir and off the heat.

Transition Phase - Day 33. Taste of Taiwan without VTL, PCR & Quarantine

Brioche French Toast from Wakey Wakey. Found in The  Concourse along Beach Road, they opened in 2018 by the group behind the popular cafÃ©s Strangersâ€™ Reunion and Curious Palette. Serving up a similar concept with slight variations in their offerings, I was curious to taste their food having dined previously at the latter brand. It allured me with the item that was always my weakness at brunches, and I had probably eaten my fair share of.

Bread: 7.5/10. A deep brown exterior on both the toasts showed promise of a crisp texture, and delivered a well made crunch without being too crumbly like biscuits. It was also supported with a relatively fluffy inner texture with good moisture, absorbing the custard adequately. That said, flavours were a bit muted with the bitterness of its toast being forward, and lacked a strong synergy with the other ingredients in the dish. It could afford to be more heavy-handed with spices to enrich its profile, while complimenting and supporting the toppings

Toppings: 7/10. Opting for the sweet and savoury route was a bold move, as the complexity in achieving a nice balance was often the downfall of the attempt. A smart pairing of maple-glazed bacon and apple compote was key to its moderate success, with homemade crumble a nice finishing touch. However, I felt the added vanilla ice cream contrasted too much against the bacon, and along seasonal berries felt like another profile included into its already delicate balance. Having them separate tasted better, but contradicted the intention of putting everything on the same plate

Overall: 7.3/10. A pretty decent version of the said dish, with their well prepared toasts rightfully being the star. I appreciated the difficult attempt of serving both ends of the flavour spectrum, which almost succeeded sans the berries and ice cream. Perhaps they could create a berries and ice cream French Toast item, which I would love to see them work their magic on. $20.90++ might seem a bit steep, but a good execution made its worth.

Sid Burger from Sid Burger and Craft Beer. It opened in early 2021 along Icon Village at Tanjong Pagar, and had been on my list of burger spots to visit since. From the same group behind Vatos Urban Tacos, this small shop specialised in handcrafted burgers and craft beers, the latter being offered through its wide range. For me, the former appealed more, and seeing its rave reviews and 4.9 rating on Google made me even more keen to visit and taste the hype through its namesake burger.

Juiciness: 7/10. Made using a Wagyu and Angus blend, the patty tucked itself snugly on the bottom bun, a different presentation from the usual arrangement of being sat on fresh greens which it did not have. While I enjoyed the beefiness, its relatively small form limited how much taste it offered. Its texture was decent from the tender insides to its crisp exterior, but again hardly felt in a complete bite. Maybe a double was needed to fully enjoy the work put into its beef patties

Bun: 5.5/10. Crowned with sesame seed buns, both top and bottom undersides were lightly toasted, thoughtful to support the moisture from its other elements. Sadly, I found its inner texture too soft, that while was enough to hold up the weight, lacked the bite I craved for in buns. It was also quite plain, and could be improved by toasting them with grease or butter

Synergy: 7.5/10. Topped off with a generous serving of BBQ shredded pork, along with jalapeÃ±o relish, pickled red onions, apple coleslaw and sriracha mayonnaise, it delivered a smoky aroma and taste largely assumed to be from the pork. The heat kick of the jalapeÃ±o, onions and mayonnaise complemented and elevated flavours, with its coleslaw a refreshing balance. Supposedly had cheddar cheese, but that either melted or was omitted, and missed a binding element

Overall: 6.7/10. A decent burger, but did not impress to what I expected. There were promising aspects which I felt could built upon to become a real contender. Being a smashburger the single patty was quite off balanced, doubling it up might do the trick along with the missing cheese. A good price of $12++ during Happy Hour, its great service would bring me back for its other items.

MEME Fish & Chips from MEME Bistro Bar. A relatively new spot opened only in September 2020, they served up usual bar bites and mains in their gathering-friendly setting for an enjoyable dining experience. Being along Mackenzie Road made them a bit inaccessible, but still only a short stroll away from Little India MRT. I scrolled past some posts on them before and looked forward to tasting what they had to offer.

Fish: 7/10. Served on a giant metal platter, the fish slab had a decent coloured batter that it supposedly coined their MEME Special Batter. Not just for show, this was a good reflection of its well spiced flavour that enhanced each bite. Its thin coating compared with the fish made a good ratio, and had nice crisps and crunches with its craggy exterior. The fish was a bit too soft for me, that dampened the experience by breaking apart too easily and did not stick well to the batter

Chips: 6/10. To match the size of its fish and platter, an equally generous portion of fries cushioned the fish. Its little specks of herb were quite negligible and could do with more seasoning, while texture wise there was also nothing special about them. An average batch of fries I would not mind having but would not finish

Tartar Sauce: 6/10. Called â€œlemon sauceâ€ on its menu, I was not sure if it was really that since it looked like just mayonnaise with a pinch of the same herb used for its fries. It paired decently with the main components, but again felt almost replaceable with any generic sauce. A missed opportunity to further elevate the dish

Overall: 6.3/10. While first impressions were promising, it turned out relatively mediocre not from its execution but rather how it compared with others. It was not bad, just not impressionable to justify searching for the spot to visit. $17.90 perhaps was for its portion, I would skip this and go for something more enticing like the MEME Ultimate Burger, that already sounded like a winner.

Cod Fish Brioche Burger from Surrey Hills Grocer. This spot sat within Arena Country Club at Joo Koon, meant to mimic the experience of visiting farms in Australia. It opened recently in January 2022 with its cafe a subset of the grocer. Their menu was supposedly designed in collaboration with an Australian Michelin-starred chef, and I made the trip one day to appease my wanderlust.

Fish: 6.5/10. Instead of the usual battered and fried fish patties, they presented a relatively lighter option with a grilled cod. Without a crust to hide under, its glistening surface with nice charred marks were promising marks of good execution. The delicate nature of cod meant it flaked easily, and without an outer layer holding things together made it a bit messy. Its moistness showcased the innate flavour of the fish, but felt it was on the mild spectrum for both taste and texture 

Bun: 6.5/10. The top brioche bun sat propped ajar from the burger when served, but I was quite pleased by the glisten just like the fish it supported. Cutting through it after crowning, its surface first crackled then gave way to a soft and relatively fluffy core. Not much liquids for it to soak up meant it retained its form throughout. The buttery taste of brioche was mild, which I had hoped to be more potent to enhance the already lighter fish

Synergy: 7/10. Complementing the burger was a house made dill tartare slathered on both buns, finished with pickled green chilli, lettuce and carrots. The sauce was a nice way of incorporating the quintessential herb into the dish without eating it alone, and tartar a classic use for fish. However, the other vegetables felt awkward for their respective flavours and textures, I thought the oriental salad could work adequately as the fresh elements instead

Overall: 6.7/10. Quite a decent burger that was more an upscale version, reflecting the Australia brunch culture I missed dearly. They worked well as a break from the urban jungle with a relaxing experience, which was not that inconvenient given its short walk from the MRT. Its price was relatively high at $24++, but I assumed was for its sustainable sourcing. Hope to try items off their brunch menu next!

Chicken & Pancakes from Birdfolks. Established in late 2017, the concept started from the ownersâ€™ experience in the US that left an unforgettable impact on them. An extended period of experimenting led them to develop a unique Singapore-style instead of recreating flavour. Located in NEWest, I made the special trip to try what I had been missing out on.

Chicken: 8/10. Their signature fried chicken were made upon order, prepared with an American-style brine and batter method. They envisioned fried chicken to have a nice crust encasing the juicy meat that was achieved in this boneless thigh. Their unique spice blend made for a well flavoured mouthful, coupled with its deep brown caramelised crust delivered layers of taste and texture. I only wished for more craggy bits for an added crunch

Waffles: 6/10. Yes I know these were not waffles but its ingredients were similar but maybe in a different ratio. I thought these buttermilk pancakes had a rustic charm, its simple but consistent looks made it feel homemade. While on the flatter end, these still had a slight fluff for a nice chew to complement the crisp chicken. I wished for more flavour though as these were plain and lacked an oomph to enhance the dish as a whole

Sauce: 6/10. Served with a mini pitcher of maple syrup, the no-frills option offered some sweetness to the dish with its accompanying moisture. A subtle point, but did appreciate its segregated serving to give me control of the amounts I preferred. The butter felt more suited for the pancakes, though I did try it with the chicken out of curiosity, with minimal impact

Overall: 6.7/10. As their name suggested, they did their bird well but its other components was a bit average. If solely based on the chicken, they were probably one of the better places to visit for. Otherwise for said dish, it needed much more from its other components. Seeing other diners order their other mains like rice bowls and burgers, I would love trying them in my next visit.

Bean Curd Skin Soup with Fish Ball.

Ingredients: Bean curd, fishball, fresh shitake mushroom, garlic, salt, black pepper, white pepper, soy sauce (maggie seasoning), shaoxing wine, chicken powder, sesame oil, spring onion, coriander, and vegetable oil.

Ingredients:
White mushrooms
Shimeji mushrooms
White onions, chopped
Arborio rice
1 cup dashi stock
Butter
Sake
Italian herbs
Black pepper

Caramelise the onions in melted butter. Add the rice and coat well in the butter sauce, then the mushrooms. Stir around abit, then add sake and dashi stock. Add the Italian herbs and let it simmer for 15-17 minutes till all the stock has evaporated. Add black pepper and stir through.

Sprinkle spring onions before serving.

Ingredients:
Minced pork
Potherb mustard 
Diced mushrooms
Chopped garlic
Chopped shallots
Noodles (I used fresh ramen)

Seasoning:
1 tbsp hoisin sauce
1 tbsp doubanjiang
Dark soy sauce
Light soy sauce
Huadiao wine
Sesame oil
Pepper
Sugar

Boil the noodles till al dente and drain the water.

Stirfry the garlic and shallots, add the mushrooms and mustard, doubanjiang and hoisin sauce and blend it all together. Then add the pork mince, break it up into crumbs, then the rest of the seasonings. Add some water to make gravy and simmer. Lastly, add slurry to thicken. 

Pour the meat gravy over the noodles and garnish with sliced cucumber if you wish.

ğŸ No. 26 - Finding time to make a sourdough loaf hasnâ€™t been easy. Another loaf, another opportunity to experiment ğŸ˜‰

Ingredients :
Bread Flour 240g
Unbleached All-Purpose Flour 60g
Water 240g
Levain 60g (starter was fed 1:1:1)
Salt 6g

Method:
- Autolyse starter, flour and water, for 1 hour
- Add Salt 
- Rest 10 minutes
- Stretch and Fold, once
- Rest 30 minutes
- Coil Fold 3 sets, 40 minutes interval
- Rest the dough for at least 1 hour before shaping
- Preshape the dough
- Rest 20 minutes
- Shape the dough
- Rest the dough in the banneton basket for 20 minutes
- Cold Retard 14 hours at 1-3Â°C
- Place dutch oven in the oven and preheat at 250Â°C
- Bake covered at 250Â°C for 23 minutes, and bake another 17 minutes at 230Â°C uncovered
- Cool for at least 3 hours before slicing

Argentinian Prawn Pasta? I didnâ€™t expect the Argentinians to do pasta, but I really shouldnâ€™t be that surprised considering that pasta is pretty much a universal dish. While it is neither a hundred percent Italian or Argentinian, @tonito.singapore piquant prawn pasta is definitely a hundred percent exquisite.â €
â €
Silky strands of spaghetti done al dente are bathed luxuriously in a palatable pomodoro sauce, and fortified with two titanic Argentinian prawns, littleneck clams & shredded crabmeat. The sauce is a textbook example of how to do an excellent pomodoro : smooth, thick, garlicky, and jam packed full of satisfying savouriness with just a little sweet & sourness to shake it up. Just the perfect sauce for the pasta.â €
â €
As one would expect of any self respecting restaurant, all of the seafood on the plate were commendably fresh. The huge prawns still retained their subtle sweetness, but now boasted a newly acquired smokiness from being grilled expertly. Garlic & prawns are a match made in heaven, and this is definitely seventh heaven. I mean, the prawns are comprehensively blanketed by fried garlic. Unless youâ€™re Dracula, thatâ€™s Flavortown on the back of a couple of prawns.â €
â €
As for the clams & crabmeat, they donâ€™t add much in the way of flavour, but they definitely complete the dish and give it a sublimely satisfying weight. The crabmeat in particular will ensure that almost no mouthful is purely pasta and nothing else. Nossir, the carbs are completed by all the deeply satisfying seafood that rounds it all out. If youâ€™re ravenously hungry and have an insatiable craving for pasta, this ponderous plate of prawn pasta is just what you need.â €

Thatâ€™s right, TWO of these Argentinian beauties for the low, LOW price of $26++! Now, Iâ€™m crying for this Argentinian prawn pasta, but they are most definitely joyful tears.â €
â €
Thank you so much for the invite, @tonito.singapore and @burpple!

If these fried fish were to be taken on their own, it would merely be decent as opposed to spectacular. The dessert course of the brilliant #burpplebeyond is @tonito.singapore very special Chocolate Tres Leche cake, which sees a slab of spiced chocolate cake sparingly garnished with some candied pistachios, a couple of blueberries, whipped cream and lubed up by the puddle of tres leches, which is a triple threat of condensed milk, evaporated milk, and heavy cream. Yes, this is a choccy milk cake.â €
â €
Tres leches cake is traditionally a sponge cake, but this one was a very intriguing cross between a mousse and a sponge cake, flavoured with slightly bitter dark chocolate. The spice component is very mild, with just fleeting hints of cinnamon & nutmeg flitting over your palate as you devour this wet little sweetie. The sweetness is extremely subtle here, and most of the sugar rush actually comes from the tres leche mix as opposed to the cake itself.â €
â €
The Chocolate Tres Leche is a subtle dessert, but it does more than enough to satisfy moderate dessert cravings. A suitable swan song to a sublime set menu if you ask me, and the pleasure of the Burpple Beyond set is heightened by the knowledge that it only costs $58++.â €
â €
Mucho gracias for hosting us, @tonito.singapore & @burpple!â €

OOZEY grainy black sesame paste sandwiched between two crisp-thin slices of bread, this Black Sesame Toast ($3.50) from @coffeebreakamoy is one that rivals my favourite Kaya Butter Toast from Ya Kun! ğŸ¤¤âœ¨ I especially loved how their black sesame paste had a more liquid-like consistency as compared to the thick kind! However, I felt that the black sesame paste was on the sweeter side and I would have preferred it less sweet. You can also never go wrong with butter in toast ğŸ˜

My friend and I also ordered their earl grey cream toast ($3.50) which features bread prepared the same way but with a filling made of earl grey infused whipped cream ğŸ˜Œ This was quite delicious, but I'm still a black sesame kind of gal ğŸ¤ª

Ordered the black sesame kopi which was disappointing because it was literally just grainy black sesame in kopi (and the black sesame sinks right to the bottom). The black sesame didn't add any flavour whatsoever to the kopi at all, but it was $3.50 for a cup ğŸ¥¶

On the flip side, the butter pecan vanilla ($4.50) we ordered was super delicious ğŸ˜‹ It tasted like a Starbucks drink (but cheaper!) - sweet and creamy!

Overall, I would be back to have my black sesame toast fix again and again, but I wouldn't get their black sesame kopi ğŸ˜— They also serve many other unique flavours of toast and drinks, which I would be back to try!

Glutinous Rice Bowl < ç³¯ç±³é¥­>
This delicious sticky rice is packed with meat, mushrooms, dried shrimps, fried shallots, and premium lap cheong (Chinese sausages)ğŸ¤â¤ï¸

Recipe (5-6 servings)
Ingredients:
- 3 cups glutinous rice, soak for at least 3 hours
- 6 dried mushrooms, soaked and sliced 
- 80g-100g dried shrimps, soaked and minced
- 300g pork or chicken, cubed
- 2 Chinese sausages, sliced and roasted 
- 4 shallots, chopped 
- Free onion, chopped 
- Cooking oil, salt, oyster sauce, sesame oil, light and dark soy sauce, pepper, water or chicken stock (I estimated the amount used)

â–ªï¸Marinate meat with oyster sauce, sesame oil, light soy sauce and pepper.  Chill it for at least 2 hours.
â–ªï¸ Prepare seasonings in a bowl - oyster sauce, light and dark soy sauce, salt  and pepper.  Combine well. Keep aside for use later. 
â–ªï¸In a heated wok, add oil and sautÃ© separately the chopped shallots, mushrooms, dried shrimps and meat.
â–ªï¸Add drained glutinous rice and continue to sautÃ© with all the ingredients for a couple of minutes until well combine. 
â–ªï¸Add seasonings and continue to sautÃ© for about ten minutes. 
â–ªï¸Add water bit by bit as you sautÃ©.
â–ªï¸Turn off heat and drizzle with sesame oil. 
â–ªï¸Transfer to a big bowl and steam it in a steamer on high heat for 30 minutes. 
â–ªï¸Use chopsticks to fluff the rice and drizzle more water. 
â–ªï¸Close the steamer lid and let it steamed for another 15 minutes. Turn off heat and let it cool in the steamer until serving time. 
â–ªï¸Add roasted Chinese sausages or lap cheong on the rice. Garnish with cut green onion. 
â–ªï¸Served it with homemade chili and stir-fried veggie of your choice. Enjoy!

Itâ€™s a snoozy mid-week and I decided to get a cuppa from @bimbocoffeesg! Ended up ordering a couple of them as I could not make up my mind and the plethora of coffee offerings at @bimbocoffeesg were just too tempting!!

Bimbo Coffee offers the conventional coffee like black and white coffee and also really unique flavours like yuzu and cinnamon. The coffee is brewed to order and the flavours are infused by the Bimbos themselves! The beans that they used are chosen carefully to match the different profiles and they use a variety of beans for different flavours to bring out the best in each of their coffee!

I tried the rose, mint, melon and red dates flavoured coffees and also their white coffee! You can choose whether you would like to have your coffee sweetened or unsweetened when you order them. My favourite would have to be the red dates coffee because the coffee is slightly on the stronger side and leaves my caffeine cravings satisfied!

Do check out the handcrafted coffees @bimbocoffeesg if you are longing for some caffeine shots or a cuppa creamy coffee!

Spicy Thai Chicken Indomie

@Indomisg  has a special taste and enjoyment. You don't need a lot of additional seasoning to feel the pleasure. Add a little topping like Thai-style chicken which is spicy and delicious with a sunny side up on top will be so perfect

Full recipe below:

1 serving

Ingredients 
1 pkt. Indomie Mi Goreng Original
150 gr Minced Chicken
1 pcs. Chili Padi
1 pcs. Large Chilli 
Â¼ pcs White Onion 
2 Cloves Garlic 
3 Stalks Holy Basil Leaves 
1tbsp Soy Sauce
1tbsp Oyster Sauce
2tbsp Fish Sauce
Â½ tbsp Sugar 
1 pcs egg

Cooking the Indomie
	1.	Boil noodles for 3 mins
	2.	Put seasoning on plate, drain noodles once cooked, and mix well.	

Spicy Thai Chicken
	1.	Add cooking oil to the pan
	2.	Using medium heat, sautÃ© garlic, onion, large chili, and chili padi until fragrant 
	3.	Add in minced chicken, 
	5.	Pour in Soy Sauce, Oyster Sauce, Fish Sauce, and Sugar.
	6.	Stir until the chicken is cooked, turn off the heat 
	9.	Add in holy basil leaves stir for 30 secs
	10.	Serve with Indomie Mi Goreng Original and sunny side up

Sometimes, the small little things can be touching too!

My friends and I arranged a gathering on Sunday and so happened that my hubby has an official meeting and couldn't take care of our son, so I decided to bring my son along with me for the lunch gathering. During the lunch, my friends teased my son asking if he brought money to pay for the meal. My son replied that he did want to bring his wallet but daddy said that mummy will have less worries if I don't bring money. Later on, when I got home, my hubby told me actually our son did plan on dipping into his piggy bank so that he could bring enough money to take care of his mummy. Oh....so sweet of him! And, during the meal, he was on his best behaviour throughout and making sure that everyone had a good time.

Dish of the day @mouthrestaurant :
Mouth-watering dim sum includes Salted Egg Yolk Bun (Must Try! Life-changing, so good), Crispy Chopstick Prawn (Crispy and delicious), Deep Fried Prawn Dumplings, Pan Fried Beancurd Roll (one of my favourite dish), Egg Tart (my son's favourite dish) and steamed Prawn Siew Mai etc.

Every day can be a fresh start!
Do not like the way things have been going, why not just start afresh and find ways to fix things until you like them!

Grocery shopping used to be a chore as have to go to different places to get the best deals for different things, now everything can be shopped online and delivered, so much time and money saved.

@tankfullyfresh - they delivered fresh and frozen seafood to your doorstep and even offer free delivery above $60. 
1. 150 - 200g of codfish- fresh and no fishy smell, so suitable for steaming.
2. 500 - 600g of red snapper - the fish comes fresh and already thoroughly cleaned, so no hassle to have to de-gill and clean the fish yourself. Can just rinse and it is ready to steam.
3. Canada Scallop 200 - 240g - Fresh and soft, not chewy or rubbery at all.
4. Frozen Tiger Prawn 1kg - juicy prawns

Thank you @thefitureco for arranging & @tankfullyfresh for the seafood.

Make time to listen to each other!

Sometimes, when we are home and busy with our own stuff, we hardly pay attention to what the people around us are saying. My hubby always says that he told me something already but I have no recollection of it at all! Sometimes I even think he might be hallucinating - Who did he actually tell the message to? 

So, a good idea is to have a nice sit down meal and switch off all devices so that we can listen to each other attentively.

@booncafe.sg @itespore:
1. Curry chicken with country loaf - SGD6.00. The country loaf is so fluffy and nice, if only the cafe can help to heat it up a bit will be perfect.
2. Cafe Breakfast - SGD7.00. Fluffy egg with the same nice country loaf and a nicely dressed salad.
3. Black coffee - SGD2.50. The freshly ground coffee aroma is totally awesome.

Is the season of the year again where we are blessed with all the nice cuisines and joyous people around us.

Happy Chinese New Year to all in advance.

Thank you @botanictsg for sharing this Nonya CNY Special:
1. Babi Pongteh - The Babi is a mixed of Soya and Konnyaku.
2. Sambal Pentai Seafood - The seafood are made of Konnyaku to give a chewy texture and this is one of my favourite as the sambal is so good.
3. Ayam Buah Keluak - Ayam is made of gluten and is so flavourful with the unique taste of the Buah Keluak.
4. Nonya Curry Fish Head - The fish head is made of beancurd and seaweed. It absorbed the appetising gravy very well for a fantastic taste explosionon my tongue. 

All dishes are allium free and plant based. Good not only for vegetarians but for anyone taking a break from meat!

Iâ€™cook Dinner: Giant Scallops & Prawn Dumpling Ramen in Tonkotsu Broth with Greens.
*
These scallops are 2 inches in diameter. Very sweet. Defrost and just simmer them in the tonkotsu broth. My tonkotsu broth is home-made from pork bones. You can use a pressure cooker to make a batch and then freeze. Added some dashi to boost the umami flavours. The prawn dumplings were wrapped in advance and frozen. Just cook them when needed. Noodles cook briefly for 40sec and then quench in cold water to maintain the QQ texture of the noodles. Assemble all ingredients and pour the broth over. Sprinkle over spring onions and sesame seeds as garnish.
*

description:
Iâ€™review: Yi Sheng Prawn Hokkien Mee, ABC Brickworks Hawker Center.
*
This prawn noodles stall at ABC Brickworks hawker is actually quite famous. Today i see, wha, only 2 people Q-ing faster buy. End up waiting for 35min because there is a snaking invisible Q. Partly because the uncle cook slowly for the wok hei and only do a few plates at a time instead of one whole wok together. The uncle is frail and the auntie got attitude. Will probably loose this stall in 10 years. The wok hei is there and the taste of the gravy is not bad seriously. But at $5, there is only 2 tiny prawns so i feel short changed. You can tell from the greyish brown colour of the gravy, there is wok hei and there is char. The smells is not bad. The chilli spiciness is also just right. But will i wait 35min for this? I donâ€™t think so. Itâ€™s very good plate of Hokkien mee but it is not in the WOW category. If you want to be wowed, try the wow wow west.
*
Price: $5 nett
Rating: 7.9/10
*

description:
Iâ€™review: Fong Sheng Char Kway Teow, Bukit Merah Hawker Center.
*
Itâ€™s hard to find good char kway teow these days. The hawkers are all of age and retired and this food heritage is going extinct. The taste profile is pretty good overall. The wok hei of this CKT is not bad. There is this wok hei taste but i think it can be slightly better. More chat nicer. I like the fact that this is not super oily and the beansprouts is a nice touch. The cockles are plum and juicy. Not a bad choice.

Celebrating my dear friend @sandy_lavignedor and my birthday at Claudine Restaurant. 

I would like to call this restaurant @chef_julien Royerâ€™s (of 3 stars Odette) home kitchen.  The restaurant name is homage to his dear mother and the food inspired by his childhood memories of his motherâ€™s recipe and traditional French dishes. The menu is extensive and the main courses are designed to be shared, just like in a family meal. I get intimidated by food so fanciful I donâ€™t know what I am eating or have to guess. Thankfully the dishes here are straight forward and come with multi-layers of texture and flavor. So guessing a bit of the ingredients needed but it is fun as you try to re-engineer the recipe!

Corkage policy here is 1 for 1. There are some wines here that are pretty reasonably marked up. In fact I saw a Champagne that was priced lower than I bought retail! I guess importing their own wines helped with that. 

Menu:
Organic Egg Forestiere- A panko crusted egg over baby spinach, black truffle vinaigrette and topped with 40 months parmesan shavings had me mopping up the sauce and yolk so clean, the server who came back to clear the plate thought he send me an empty plate!

Saint-Nectaire Croquettes- topped with a dallop of savory Vin Jaune gel and filled with umami-licious oozy cheese from Auvergne. I think the standard serving should be 6 and not 4. 

Chou Farci - Stuffed Cabbage stew. Stunning! I will need to find words to describe it. I will dedicate another post just on this. 

Pariterole- I wished for a dessert out of the kitchen, and not a cheese selection as suggested. It was lovely! Vanilla cream, textured by the pecan praline and the crust with lavish dark chocolate sauce, I prefer this over a cake!

Good morning and Breakfast is ready ğŸŒğŸŒ

Well, as a wise man once said, practise makes perfect. Therefore, I am practising my bread baking again. This time, to begin with my experiment, I added 5 more grams of water to the original recipe into the dough. I want to achieve a super fluffy and soft bread. 

During the kneading process, after the dough had fully absorbed the butter, the dough became more sticky as I kneaded it. I panicked for a moment.

However, I didnâ€™t give up, otherwise I wouldnâ€™t have any bread to eat ğŸ˜‚ So, I continued kneading the dough nonstop by using both the stretch-and-fold, as well as the slap-and-fold methods. It took me quite awhile before I was able to knead the dough till it was smooth. I also used abit more oil this time to assist me with the sticky dough. Oil is good for this soft bread as it locks in the moisture of the dough.

I want to perfect this versatile sweet dough bread so that I can add different kinds of fillings for my daily consumption. I will then move on to more challenging bread types.

Here is my version of the sweet bread with additional 5 grams of water. I inserted some pork jerky as fillings for this bread. Super soft and fluffy, I like it! Self bake is definitely superior to store-bought, as it is cheaper, healthier and more hygienic. 

Will be trying other bread designs soon, Akan Datang in Malay, coming soon in English.

Happy Sunday to all here.
.

I used to eat this for lunch during my school days in a nearby coffeeshop next to the school. Sadly, this coffeeshop is no longer in existence. However, some good food memories will linger in your mind for the rest of your life. Do you have such an experience or is it just me? 

All of a sudden, a craving for this curry beef noodle returned to haunt me. I just have to cook this dish to satisfy my cravings. 

Finally, this is very own version of the curry beef brisket noodle. To be honest, I canâ€™t really recall the taste of a dish that I have tasted donkey years ago, but I remember it being so good. Humbly speaking, I had my cravings satisfied with my version of the melt in mouth curry beef brisket with noodle it was really yummylicious. I will definitely cook this dish again. Simply irresistible.

Splurged on steak for the first time and it was a wonderful experience. Read lots of raving reviews on this place thatâ€™s been conferred one of the best steakhouses in Singapore. I went for the Tajima Wagyu Tenderloin after discussing the price with my wallet. They age their own beef and grill their meats over an Argentinian Parilla which Iâ€™ve learnt is not very commonly done. I had mine medium rare and because of the aging process in the cabinet, the red juices (myoglobin + water) doesnâ€™t ooze out of the meat when you cut into it. Every bite was a delight, full of flavor and juiciness. Yes, itâ€™s worth the damage on my wallet. 
The little bottle of palate cleanser, a mix of Bourbon whiskey and apple juice, prepares you well for the gastronomic experience before they serve you your steak. 
Iâ€™m writing in reverse order but the loaf of bread came first as an appetizer. It was warm and fluffy on the inside, crispy on the outside, and went superbly well with the butter and salt. I tried very hard not to finish it to leave space for the steak. Not to forget the shot of pumpkin soup which I also loved. 
Thoroughly enjoyed every bit of my meal! Since I was seated right in front of the open kitchen, I also enjoyed watching the chefs at work, with one feeling the music and doing little dances while she prepared her dishes.

All Day Breakfast Club @ HV! 7.5/10 affordable and decent quality in general, portions pretty big too!! I got the:

3. Pink Lemonade

Loved the pancakes because they were so soft, fluffy and slightly sweet ğŸ˜‹ğŸ˜‹ scrambled eggs were creamy and the potatoes were fried well with seasoning that tasted like Calbee chips HAHA. I felt like the Rosti was generally well fried but I remembered MarchÃ©'s one to be better, loved how the sour cream complemented it and wished there was more! I also really enjoyed the pink lemonade because its a good refreshing drink that went well with the heavy meal, plus it was super cute that there was a layer of sugar coating the top part of the drink ğŸ˜ƒ retro vibes bit service a bit ğŸ¤”ğŸ¤”

HELLO GUYS WEâ€™LL FINALLY BACK WITH BREADY REVIEWS ğŸ˜

âœ¨Steepâœ¨

1.  French toast ($17)
Comprised of broiche, mascarpone, berry compote, maple granola, fresh fruits, toasted almonds and HONEY THYME SYRUP. This dish did live up to its expectations with the super fluffy and soft broiche. The best part was prob the mascarpone bc it was mild but managed to balance the overall sweetness of the dish. We recommend trying the honey thyme syrup on its own first to see if you like it before drizzling. Tbh on its own, the honey thyme syrup tasted nice to us but might be a bit too much when drizzled onto the French toast which is already sweet on its own. The syrup also tends to bring out the sourness of the berries so drizzle at your own risk âš ï¸ HAHAHA

2. Grilled cheese ($11) 
The grilled cheese was perfectly toasted without any burnt parts. The two types of cheeses (smoked cheddar and Edam) added another layer of dimension to the taste. The caramelized onions ğŸ§… were a great addition. Overall all the flavours came together really well! We recommend to eat this fresh and hot ğŸ‘ŒğŸ»

All in all, we used burpple and it came down to $20 in total (+ additional $0.30 for iced water) which we felt was really worth it given the big portion served and standard of the food!

description:
@downstairs_sg (by @songfabkt) has probably one of the most affordable meals that you could get at @sunteccity! 

We tried:
â€¢ Lu Rou Fan $6.00
â€¢ Salted Egg Chicken Nasi Lemak $8.90
â€¢ Kaya Butter Toast Bun $2.60
â€¢ Kopi/Teh $1.30 each 

Lu Rou Fan (aka braised pork belly rice) with lava egg is reasonably priced and comes in a legit portion. The pork belly is pretty well braised and has a good combination of lean meat and fats, very well marinated and braised, thus giving a tender texture!Â  I also like how they added a generous portion of the pickled sour mustard to this dish, its savoury and sourness does helps to balance the greasiness of the braised pork and also opens up your appetite for more food! ğŸ˜†

Salted Egg Chicken Nasi Lemak on other hand wasnt really what i would prefer. The rice is light, fluffy with nice coconut fragrance and pretty flavourful. But the crispy chicken was tough and the batter was kinda thick. The salted egg sauce is smooth but comes with very subtle salted egg taste. But the sambal chilli was pretty good though. 

The toast bun is fluffy, but not those toasted crispy ones if you expecting for those. But its still pretty good to go with a cup of kopi and teh with it! 

ğŸ½ Downstairs

Heard so much rave about @syip.sg's tiramisu and I thought I should give it a try since tiramisu is easily one of my favourite desserts!

We tried:
â€¢Â Kahlua Tiramisu $10++
â€¢Â Creamy Chicken Scrambled Egg Croissant $16++

The Kahlua Tiramisu is a super comforting treat for anyone who loves Tiramisu! My favourite tiramisus are usually those containing kahlua (coffee liqueur), especially those that has a good balance between coffee and alcohol! Cause very importantly, Kahlua elevates the coffee aromas! IMO, this Tiramisu pretty much fits the bill! The coffee liqueur steeped sponge fingers taste like an almost perfect balance of the coffee and alcohol. Its further nicely completed with smooth mascarpone cream that has great consistency between fluffy and mousse-like. I know itâ€™s a sinful indulgence, but I bet you will be just like me â€“ canâ€™t stop after the first spoon. Lol.Â  

Creamy Chicken Scrambled Egg Croissant features a croissant blanketed with the creamy chicken, mushroom, and soft scrambled egg. The croissant itself is not too bad, its fluffy and fragrant. When eaten together with chicken & mushroom pieces and soft scrambled egg, it gives a very full bodied and rich texture. But tbh, I donâ€™t think itâ€™s a very special dish, but probably still worth giving it a try anyway. :)

ğŸ½ SYIP

TAIWANESE FOOD
How can we not order the 3 bowls set when the eatery is named Eat 3 bowls?

What the 3 bowls consisted of:
â€¢Braised Pork Rice
With a good mix of fatty bits, it gives the melt in your mouth feel. The rice had generous amounts of gravy too. Tasty.

â€¢Shredded Chicken Rice
Shredded chicken topped with fried shallots atop a bowl of rice. I was pleasantly surprised that the rice was drenched in sauce. Not at all dry and so appetising. Comfort food.

â€¢Oyster Pork Intestine Mee Suah
The Mee Suah broth was a bit on the watery side, not too starchy (I actually like it this way). The Mee Suah was firm and not too mushy. Served with braised pork intestines, a piece of plump oyster and a dollop of minced garlic. Delish.

Also added on sides of egg and braised cabbage ğŸ¤©

Our choice of drinks:
~Fresh Milk with Grass Jelly - check out the glass full of grass jelly! But would request for less sweet next round. Like that they serve with metal straw too.

~Iced Coffee - the coffee is in the form of a piece of ice shaped like a polar bear on ice. The coffee will melt into the milk to give you ice coffee. Cute!

Overall, enjoyed the food and will be back again. However, we over-ordered for 2 pax this round. Will order lesser next time!

So yesterday, my dad and I took leave to spend the afternoon together. It has been perhaps 2 decades since we last spent time one-on-one talking and just enjoying time together. Then, it was my dad bringing me to the playground and playing with me. Yesterday, it was 2 ways â€“ us catching up on each othersâ€™ lives and talking about the mini adventure/journey Iâ€™ll be embarking on in a few monthsâ€™ time. 

The time spent was particularly significant to me â€“ having worked for a few years, I started to catch a microcosm of what my dad (and my mum) do just to provide for the family. It was no longer the idea of â€˜parents making sacrificesâ€™ that I thought of when I was younger, but rather, it actually hit me how much it actually mean â€“ time, finances, housing, car, vacations (air tickets, accommodations, food), insurance, food, medical and other bills and taxes, the activities my sisters and I want to learn (ballet, piano, Chinese calligraphy, arts and craft, and others..) and their love and care despite having only a mere 24h just like everyone else. 

To my dad who hardly says â€˜noâ€™ to me, to my dad who says instead, â€˜lets try thisâ€™, â€˜lets goâ€™, â€˜(lets do it) for the experienceâ€™, â€˜lets have funâ€™, â€˜(not to) be penny-wise and pound-foolishâ€™, to my dad who always remind me 'it's the memories and the people that count, rather than the things (materials / food / places)', and to my dad who supports me in the various things I do (despite not exactly agreeing / being concern, such as my â€˜new journeyâ€™), words canâ€™t express how I truly feel. 

Thanks daddy <3

(Last pic: we arrived and my dad's phone rang... and he had to answer a work call ğŸ¥², thankfully there wasn't any other calls for that afternoon)

After trying @noce.nuts â€™s hazelnut butter, when @kneadandpinch approached me about her bread and how she would be incorporating @noce.nuts â€˜s cashew nut butter, I was rly excited! 

Featured here is @kneadandpinch â€˜s Walnut Cashew Banana Bread ($26 - family size). As a huge fan of nuts, @kneadandpinch â€˜s version of banana bread is definitely an elevation of the usual ones. Imagine the lovely crunch of walnuts within the banana loaf that adds texture to the otherwise soft and moist bread. Thatâ€™s not all, now add to your imagination the crisp and freshness of almond flakes sprinkled on a drizzle of @noce.nuts â€˜s cashew butter, atop the banana bread. Can you feel the nuttiness of this banana bread!! I love @kneadandpinch â€™s creativity in incorporating not only the usual walnuts, but also cashews (in terms of butter) and almonds (in the form of flakes) into her bread â€“ this is definitely the first for me. Besides this, you can expect the combination of textures, from the soft and moist banana bread to the crunchy walnuts, the crispy almond flakes, and finally the creamy and rich cashew butter. Taste-wise, I found the banana flavour not as strong as I expected, and this makes her banana bread more acceptable by a larger audience, where those who donâ€™t fancy banana might be able to accept â€“ like my mum who not only accepts but finds the cake nice. What I particularly appreciate is how @kneadandpinch does not skimp on the ingredients and the generous amount of nuts in her bread is definitely a selling point to a nut lover like myself. Additionally, I also like how her bread has just the right sweetness which makes it great for breakfast, supper, or tea.

In 2021, I brought my family to 2 of my favourite cafes from 2020: Wild Honey and Nassim Hill. And in 2022, I decided to bring my family to The Assembly Ground!!

We went for lunch as I wanted to try the brunch options, particularly the Rosti Benedict and Southern Chicken & Waffles. Was a lil disappointed when we were told the Rosti was OOS.. But nonetheless, we enjoyed the other options and the service was good as usual! 

â€¢ Truffle Carbonara â™¡ $24++
Love this so much the previous time, I had to order this this round for my family to try!! -- and it didn't disappoint, just how lovely the Truffle tasted and the texture of the noodles as I recalled them to be. (Refer to my previous post on @theassemblyground to find out more!)
"fettuccine, shiitake & white button mushrooms, porcini cream sauce, poached egg, shaved parmigiano, truffle paste"

â€¢ Crab Pomodoro â™¡ $24++
Another item that I had to order again this round. Love the spicy kick and the generous chunks of legit crab meat that I remembered it for. (Refer to my previous post)
"Spaghetti, Jumbo Lump Crabmeat, Shaved Parmesan, Spicy Pomodoro Sauce with a touch of Cream"

â€¢ Southern Chicken and Waffle $22++
Ordered without looking at the photo or reading the description and was surprised to see the waffle as a charcoal one! Was surprise after tasting the waffle -- there seems to be honey on the inside. While it's nice on it's own, it might be a tad too sweet for those who intend to have it tgt with the chicken. Quite a worth item to get especially if you love variety in your food! It consisted of buttermilk fried chicken, charcoal waffle, potato gratin, served with a side of salted egg yolk sauce, maple syrup and butter. 

â€¢ Umami Roasted Chicken â™¡ $23++
This was like SO GOOD?? We initially didn't plan to order this but we're so glad we did. Lovely pizza crust that felt somewhat laminated and reminds me so much of a croissant. The ingredients were plentiful and the whole pizza was of a good size and so flavourful. Would definitely order this again.

Perfect end to a lovely meal!

because I think they are sublime

pair this with rice and there goes a flavor explosion in your mouth 

chinese style lemon chicken ğŸ“ 
INGREDIENTS
250g chicken breast,washed, pat dry and cut into bite-sized pieces
Â½ tbsp soy sauce 
2 clove minced garlicğŸ§„ 
1 eggğŸ³ 
salt and pepper to tasteğŸ§‚ 
lemon zestğŸ‹ 
3 tbsp corn starch

for the sauce
1 tbsp of oil
2 cloves minced garlic
90ml water 
lemon juice from half a lemonğŸ‹ 
2-3 tbsp sugarğŸ¬
1 tbsp soy sauce 
1 tsp vinegar
1 tbsp honeyğŸ¯ 
lemon zest (optional)
2 lemon slices
cornstarch slurry(mix 2 tbsp water with 1 tsp cornstarch) 
 
for garnish
sesame seeds
chopped green onionğŸ§… 

STEPS
1.marinate chicken with soy sauce, salt and pepper, garlic,ginger,egg and corn flour and mix well until chicken is well coated, set aside for an hour

2.in a pan, heat about 1 inch deep of oil and fry chicken for 7-8 minutes or until golden brown.set chicken aside

3.to make the sauce, heat 1 tbsp of oil in another pan and fry garlic till fragrant (not burnt) then add water ,lemon juice,soy sauce, vinegar, sugar, honey, lemon slices and lemon zest 

4.taste test now to check if sauce is too sour, if it is too sour, add in another additional 1 tbsp of sugar

5. remove lemon slices

6.at this point, add in your cornstarch slurry and boil for 6-7 minutes or longer and mix occasionally until sauce thickens

7.mix the chicken well with the sauce 

8.garnish,serve with rice and enjoy â˜ºï¸

kuih keria ğŸ  
malaysia sweet potato donut 
INGREDIENTS
250 g orange sweet potato peeled and sliced
pinch of salt for boiling potatoes 
1 tbsp glutinous rice flour
80-100 g all-purpose flour, depending on how wet your sweet potatoes are, so agar agar it and go by feeling

sugar coating
2 tbsp white sugar
2 tbsp water
flour for dusting at the end, to prevent sugar coating from dissolving when it cools 

STEPS
1.cook sweet potatoes in boiling water for about 10 minutes or until soft
2.drain the potatoes and mash them up 
3.mix in rice flour and all-purpose flour and knead till you get a dough, the amount of flour you add depends on how wet or dry your sweet potatoes are, you should get a soft and not so sticky dough
4.with greased hands, cut dough into 8 and roll them into balls
5.poke a hole in the center with your finger to create a donut shape, and repeat with the rest of the dough 
6.pour about 1 inch of cooking oil to a pan and fry the donuts for about 7-10 minutes, flipping regularly( if bubbles form on chopsticks, the donuts are ready to fry)
7.to another the pan, add sugar and water. 
8.stir constantly, until the sugar dissolves and the mixture becomes bubbly and thick, turn off the heat and add in the fried donuts and make sure they are well coated in the sugar mixture
9.sprinkle some flour over donuts and mix. now, the sugar liquid should have changed into a sand-like consistency.
10.let cool slightly before serving and enjoyâ˜ºï¸â˜ºï¸

ğŸ“Cold Storage at Compass One
ğŸš‡ Sengkang

I'm really loving the refreshed Cold Storage at Compass One! It's not just beautiful, it's sustainable as well. Fun fact: Their counter fronts are made from reclaimed wood and most of the fixtures are clad in bamboo! 

For those who know me, you'll know that I'm calorie conscious 5 days a week, so that I can eat anything I like on my cheat days. Yong Tau Fu is definitely one of my go-to healthy meal choice. I appreciate that there are over 50 ingredients I can choose from the Fresh Yong Tau Fu Station so that I can be pick ingredients I like and watch my waist line at the same time.

Steam fish is one of my mum and grandma's favourite dish to cook as they believe it's nutritious and good for the body. They were happy to see the wide variety of fishes they can choose from. Plus, Cold Storage offers free prep services such as descaling, deboning, fillet and more. The staff over the counter were very friendly and helpful. You can just let them know what you're cooking and they will prep for you! 

Truly enjoyed my grocery run at the newly refurbished Cold Storage at Compass one! Come visit and have a great shopping experience like me!

Searching through my album and found these back log that I had yet to post.

I was offered by @awfullychocolatebakeryandcafe to try out their Bakery Club Brunch at 50% its usual rate.

It was an awfully awesome brunch that started chocolaty with their Really Fresh Chocolate Milk served first, made with awfullychocolate 100% Premium Dark Cocoa freshly frothed with premium chilled Hokkaido milk.

Next, we were surprised by The Bakery Club Fresh Bread, with Roasted Aubergina baked upon ordering and cut right on our table infront of our eyes. The aroma that got into our nose are overwhelming.

The Truffle Cream Eggs was then served immediately. 

Overall, we were really in love with their bread and I am so happy to see their â€œ[Members Only] FREE Bread Tasting with our Head Baker!â€ email in my inbox this week that I am going to head there tomorrow. ğŸ˜Š

description:
ğŸ“Old Habits CafÃ© 
2 Telok Blangah Way SAFRA Mt Faber #01-04 S098803

Old Habits CafÃ© is located 2.4km away from Harbourfront MRT Station, hidden jn Safra Mt Faber.

This nostalgic cafÃ© definitely gonna bring you back in times and stir up some of our childhood memories.

As I thought we will be just indulging in the unique vintage ambiance, their food surprised me too.

Here are what we had tried last night:

- Sesame Crusted Tuna Steak ($18.90)
This steak is crusted with sesame on the outside and rare in the centre. This made it warm with crisp on the outside, cooler at room temperature in the mid, easy to chew upon and almost feel like they melt in your mouth. Dipping the tuna in their homemade sesame sauce add on to the umami and elevate it to the next level.

- Classic Chicken Chop ($9.90)
Although its called the classic chicken chop, itâ€™s definitely better than what you had in your western food stall. The chicken thigh was well roasted to char, coated with their homemade seasalt caramel sauce, each bite into it is tender, juicy and flavourful. 

- Old Habits Coconut Kueh (Pouffle) ($9.50)
First time seeing a â€œPouffleâ€ and decided to go for it. â€œItâ€™s texture between a Bread Pudding and Souffle, hence "Pouffle". Aromatic Shredded Coconut, Topped with Vanilla Bean Ice-creamâ€ as described on the menu. I canâ€™t add on my description but this is how real it is and pretty much amazed us by how good it is.

Our drinks we had â€œOld Habits Floatâ€ & their â€œHome Brewed Kiwi and Strawberry Teaâ€.
Old Habits Float is actually Rum & Raisin Ice-Cream on Kickapoo. Kiwi and Strawberry Tea carries their flavours well. Both drinks are so refreshing.

We love our time here pretty much enjoying our delicious dinner with the nostalgic ambiance. Many thanks @oldhabitssg for the very warm welcoming service that make us feel really comfortable in your cosy place. ğŸ™‡ğŸ»â€â™€ï¸

Thank you @getkobe for the invite and introducing this hideout to us.

AUTHENTIC RUSSIAN DELIGHTS IN TANJONG PAGAR!

Despite the ongoing conflict, Dumplings.Ru @dumplings.ru are certainly doing things right by acquainting more Singaporeans with the wonders of Russian-Ukrainian food.

Highlights of my meal would definitely include the Dumpling Combo Platter ($19.90+). 

12 X dumplings, 12 X different fillings such as Paneer Cheese and Minty Ram. Super IG-worthy also la, for  the dumplings like rly colourful allğŸ‘

Another star would be the Ukrainian Borscht Soup ($9.50+). 

Wah, the soup really very power, itâ€™s like thick and creamy yet so light on the tongue, v easy to swallow. Inside got stuff like pork, beetroot and tomato, and they all come together to form a crazy-good flavour combi.

The Cheese and Pork Chebureki ($12+) remind of 1x mahssive curry puff, minus the curry. Airy, crispy + savoury af, wah shiok!

If u arenâ€™t already fawning over how amazing their star dishes are, try the Salted Herring or Seledka ($12.90+) or their interesting drinks, Kompot and Kvass (from $5.50+) , that u wonâ€™t find in any kopitiam I swear

We recommend: Combo Platter, Chebureki, Seledka, Borscht Soup (wish they had a buffet for at least some of their menu items istgğŸ¤©)

Main gripe: Prices for some dishes can be a bit high 

Overall: 4.25/5 (this place definitely needs more clout, weâ€™d return again again and again)

[HOME-BASED TASTING]

CREAMY BASQUE BURNT CHEESECAKES BY ONE LAST LICK!

There was legit a time where I saw the recognisable burnt cheesecake show up on everyoneâ€™s story and it was trending for a bit until ppl got jelak and sian of it then suddenly disappear 

One Last Lickâ€™s version has to be one of the better ones out there frfr, bc they managed to get wonderful balance in their cakes la

Flavours wise, the cheese really can taste one ah say serious, balancing out the sweet well ah sweechai butterflyâ€¦

Then textures also can taste the contrast, even inside the cake siaâ€¦ what we mean by this is that the cheesy inside has both gooey and harder layers that you can actually taste. The exterior also got a bit of caramel taste, q happy can taste a bit of the burnt taste too. 

The high quality of ingredients used definitely justifies the price tag of $38.90! Itâ€™s more better and way less pricey than your usual Burnt Cheesecake for sure!

We recommend: the whole thing la just get, itâ€™s that good!

Main gripe: As with most cheesecakes, it can taste a bit jelak and repetitive after a while 

Thank you again @onelastlick.sg for sending over your wonderful Basque Burnt Cheesecake!

MICHELIN BIB GOURMAND SRI LANKAN DELIGHTS AT JALAN BESAR!

Kotuwa @kotuwa.sg blew my mind siaâ€¦

Pic 1: The Chicken Kottu ($22++) was really PACKED with a multitude of flavours and textures. 

Starts off with a lil bit of spiciness, savouriness and then the aromatic spices just hits u right outta nowhere. 

A mesmerising dish that you have to try for yourself to legit know what Iâ€™m talking about frfr

Pic 2: The Watalappam Tart ($16++) clearly had us likeğŸ¤¨ğŸ¤¨at first but it was rly built different ahâ€¦ 

A rly rich coconutty custard balanced out the rly distinct taste of cardamom in the tart, which was  such a refreshing combi!

Pic 3: Mix of Mutton Rolls and Crab Cutlet. Just get them ah, no questions asked. If u donâ€™t, confirm regret one. 

If weâ€™re talking SUPER CRISPY fried panko breaded and generous mutton and actual crab fillings, look no further already ah..

We recommend: literally anything on the menu just go try ah serious

Main gripe: some of their dishes might be on the spicier side, so I suggest u lower ur ego and politely request and hope they bring down the spiciness level of your dishes (if possible)

Overall: 4.5/5 (absolute MUST-TRY, no gimmicks here, just pure awesomeness!)

DRY SCALLION OIL NOODLES WITH FRIED PORK CHOP UNDER $15 AT HOLLAND VILLAGE!

Mian Jia Noodle Bar @mianjia_sg has these hearty, savoury scallion oil noodles that Iâ€™m straight up dying for rn. 

Topped with bonito flakes to give the dish an extra OOMPH, the noodles are flavourful throughout and their portion size also quite big.

The juicy pork chop also q generously given, with a solid crunch, gelling well with the noodles!

We recommend: Five Spice Crispy Pork Chop with Special Sauce Dry Noodle ($10.90+)

Main gripe: you might get this dehydrating feeling after a whole bowl of noodles, remember to hydrate loads too!

Overall: 4/5 (one of HVâ€™s hidden gems!)

WAGYU BEEF RICE BOWL, TOM YUM SEAFOOD PASTA AND COCONUT KUEH POUFFLE AT TELOK BLANGAH!

The ambience of Old Habits Cafe @oldhabitssg is retro  and super nostalgia evoking, as you see all sorts of knickknacks from the past when you walk in

Iâ€™d personally just return for the vibes central, transporting me back to the era of Kids Central, Anything and Whatever (IYKYK)

The Wagyu Beef Rice Bowl ($18.90) immediately caught my eye, with flamed and torched wagyu beef resting on a bed of butter rice, together with a selection of greens. 

Wah, so healthy ah, was the first thing I thought, but the healthy part was balanced out by the sinful homemade sauce served too. 

Tho I couldnâ€™t pinpoint exactly what the sauce was, it tasted mayo-like with the umaminess from mentaiko sauce, which I didnâ€™t mind at all.

The beef was on the chewy side but still robust and juicy enough for me to savour it, with their generosity being a plus point

In all honesty, the Tom Yam Seafood Pasta ($18.90) will be better known for the large amount of seafood given, rather than how appetising it was.

The sauce did have a slight sting but it lacked richness in flavour, so it was p much watery with hints of sour and spicy here and there

However, the Coconut Kueh Pouffle was a big W in our opinion

The creamy vanilla ice cream gelled well with the decadent pandan coconutty taste of the pouffle. 

A+ for creativity tho because itâ€™s literally the first time weâ€™ve seen a fusion of bread pudding and soufflÃ© in a dessertğŸ”¥ğŸ”¥ğŸ”¥

We recommend: Wagyu Beef Rice Bowl, Coconut Kueh Pouffle, coming for their AMBIENCE

Main gripe: not exactly super near an MRT, still need take bus for 10-15 mins

Overall: 3.9/5 (return for the super retro vibes and interesting menu!)

PGPR - student residence at NUS campus. My first  student dorm experience in life being 28 years old. 
The residence looks so-so outside, but well equipped and comfortable inside. 
Due to the covid - no interactions with neighbors, but it's calm and quiet, even on weekends. 
Common kitchen and bathroom that girls leave really dirty sometimes, but daily housekeeping. 
Affordable price, but takes so long to get to the city center by public transport. Also classes are online, so it doesn't make a lot of sence to stay on campus. 
No conclusion yet.

ğŸ“French fold

I went there because there was a 50% discount at their new outlet at Orchard.
This means it is a major throwback. Sorry, I'm not sorry.
Anyway, out of the 4 crepes I had, the only one worth eating is the sweet crepes. The gelato was from birds of paradise. So it's decent. 
The galettes tasted a lot like burnt chapatti. I had a hard time swallowing it down. But even with 50% off, it isn't worth it. I don't know how there's so much positive review on this. But it's clearly not for me.

So there you go. Lemon curd with maple syrup ricotta pancakes.  It's really huge and airy. Not exactly really photogenic. Plain in its own. But perfect to go with lemon curd and plenty of maple syrup. 
Cucumber gin tonic with pancakes. Cheers to the holidays.

Valentines Day 5 Course Dinner @ Hopscotch (Stamford Rd) @hopscotch_sg 

See last pic for options 

1. Lobster kueh paiti
With pork floss 
- crispy kueh paiti with a good burst of lobster umami

2. Soups 
Left - French onion soup with beef cheeks - really flavourful soft tender generous beef and delicious bread
Right - Kombu consommÃ© with scampi ravioli. Soup is meh taste like soya sauce and water but the ravioli is goood! 

3. Appetisers
A) Crabcake and guacamole
- delicious! Great combination with Thai flavours plenty of crab that is fresh in the crabcake.
B) Foie gras in hoisin glaze, hawthorn peach puree and reisling jelly
- also really delicious best part of the meal so far
- Amazing explosion of flavours

4. Mains (see photo 1 and 2)
A) Butter poached boston lobster
- very dry there's definitely not adequate butter
- chewy and not fresh
- only half a lobster and no claws provided 
Overall an extremely poorly executed lobster 

B) Herb crusted tenderloin
- herbcrust is tasteless, taste more like stuffing
- tenderloin isn't tender in the least absolutely poor marbling
- caramelised onions taste like chutney
- brandy bachamel dip was good and it saved the steak
- black garlic mash was good too but too little

5. Desserts
Left - Pandan Panna Cotta
- really good too!!! Love the gulamelaka!
Right - Cempedak keylime tart
- yumms!!! Delicious tart with fruity and citrusy notes (: delicious ending to a good meal

Overall nice atmosphere, love the rose on the table, friendly staff chill vibes. Good service. Food actually excluding the mains were really good and an amazing gastronomic experience. Unfortunately the mains are terrible ): 

Nevertheless their cocktails are really good!!! 

#valentines #steak #lobster #omakase

.

Sweet, savoury and flavourful gravy are the key to have tasty mee rebus.
Mee Rebus in Singapore have thick gravy normally but I prefer not so thick one. Instead of using dried shrimp I choose to use fresh shrimps to make more rich taste gravy.

.
.
.
.

To make the gravy
About 400gr-500gr fresh shrimps, wash and rinse clean.
1/2 cup finely grounded roasted peanut
80-100gr gula melaka, chopped.
1/2tbsp oyester sauce
2ltrs water
3pcs lemongrass  cut and smashed
2pcs kefirlime leaves
2pcs bay leaves
1pc cinnamon stick
2pcs anise star
5pcs cardamom pots

Paste to make:
10pcs shallots
5pcs garlic
4pcs candle nuts
1inch fresh gallangal
1inch fresh root ginger
1inch sand ginger
1tsp balacan paste
1tsp sweet cumin powder
Salt and pepper to taste

Instruction:
Place all ingredients in a blender, add some cooking oil. Blend until you have a fine paste.

In a large pot, add 2ltrs water, lemongrass, kefirlime leaves  cinnamon stick and the fresh shrimps. Bring to boil over high heat.

Heat some cooking oil in a sauce pan over medium fire, add the blended paste, bay leaves, anise star and cardamom pots. Fry the paste mixture until fragrant and cook for about 8-10 minutes.
Transfer the fried mixture into the hot boiling water, stir well  and continue cooking. Add the chopped gula melaka inside. Mix 1/4 cup of cornt starch + 1/4cup sweet potato starch dilute with little bit water. Reduce the heat to medium fire. Pour into the gravy and stir gently until it's throughly combined into a sauce like gravy. Next add the grounded peanut and season with oyester sauce.

To serve Mee Rebus:
Blanch Yellow noodles and beansprout (if you like) and transfer into a serving bowl.
Pour some gravy over the noodles. Add the garnish; fried tofu, boiled potato, sliced green chilli, chopped tomato, sliced spring onion and fried shallots. Top with hard boiled egg, keropok and calamansi lime halves.
Eat while warm and hot. ğŸ˜‹ğŸ˜‹ğŸ˜‹
.

Dessert of the Day, a comforting bowl of Tang Yuan with black sesame paste filling. ğŸ˜‹ğŸ˜‹ğŸ˜‹
Simple yet delicious dessert you can make in thirty-minutes.

.
.
.
.

Black Sesame Tang Yuan

Fir the filling:
120gr HollyFarms instant paste sesame powder
50gr butter, room temperature

Place the sesame powder in a small sauce pan over low heat, add the butter and stir until the butter is melted and mix well with the sesame powder.
Off the heat, roll the paste into a small ball size. Put aside.

For the glutinousrice dough
150gr glutinous rice flour
140gr warm water
Pinch of salt

Put the glutinousrice flour anf salt into a mixing bowl  slowly and gradually add the warm water while mixing. The dough should be soft and a bit sticky. Add 5gr coconut oil to keep the dough moist.
Divide the dough into 20pcs.

Bring a pot of water to a boil while preparing the tang yuan balls.

Flatten the dough with your thumb, add the filling. Gently pinch and wrap the dough. Roll into a ball shape. Gently drop the tang yuan ball into a hot boiling water, boil until the it cooked. The tang yuan balls will fliats on the surface when it cooked.
.
.
.

Truth be told that I like the rather quirky location, but not so much the food. My understanding of yakotori is that it's skewered, and grilled. The yakitori served here does not come with the familiar sight of the bamboo or metal skewers, neither do they have the the aroma of being charcoal grilled. In fact, I could almost swear the chicken skin, which came in a big piece, was deep fried. Don't get me wrong though, the food is not bad. It's just not what I would classify as yakitori. #sgrestaurant #sgfood #singaporefood #singapore #singaporerestaurant #sgfood #sg #sashimi #grilledmeat #grilledchicken #chickentail

I booked this months ago when I tried the lunch here, which left me wanting for more. I wasn't disappointed.

I'm starting to get sick of so-called Japanese restaurants helmed by non Japanese chefs, that has an "omakase menu" and tries to put an abundance of uni, caviar and/or truffle.

This, is what I yearn for. Dishes that takes much skills, cannot be easily replicated, uses seasonal and fresh ingredients which the cooking pays a lot of respect to.

The ponzu uni sauce was a stunner to begin with. To be honest this is the first time I've had shark's fin in Japanese cuisine. Combined with the abalone, the clash of the textures and flavours was just heavenly.

The deep fried hairy crab leg was another representation of perfection. From the thickness of the batter to the degree that it was fried to and the snow flakes like salt which not only add on to the aesthetics but also bring out the sweetness of the crab meat. It was so well thought out and put together.

I've always loved to learn about new ingredients and 2 stood out - nodoguro, which is a blackthroat sea perch and the hana sansho, which is a pepper flower that is available only for a couple of weeks every year. 

This, is the kind of restaurant that I look forward to going to.

It's not easy to judge a good bowl of mee rebus by its looks, so it's usually a trial and error, hit or miss situation. 

To me, a good mee rebus is almost a perfect balance - the noodles should be cooked just right and not soggy, the bean sprouts blanched to a crunch, and the most important component, the gravy, be in that middle point of being sweet and savoury, not overly thick and starchy and soupy enough to slurp it up. Bonus points with the green cut chilli and dark soya sauce (not every stall provides them, mind you).

This time, the trial and error was a big hit. Back for the second time in a week.

A satisfying lunch at Dancing Crab with my boys last week.  While most people come here for their seafood boil, some of their dishes in the menu are well worth your attention too. 

We particularly enjoyed their gumbo and the exploding crab fried rice. 

The gumbo is a meal on its own I can have it all to myself.  Delicious.  An explosion of seafood flavour.  The gravy has an intense umaminess ğŸ˜‹. I will come back for this.

The exploding fried rice has an intense wok hei and generous amount of crab meat.  The egg is a bit overdone though.  It would have been perfect if the egg yolk can drizzle over the rice grains but we love this plate of goodness nonetheless. 

The caesar salad was pretty darn good too.  Not overly dressed just perfect and I love that they grated the egg over it together with the parmesan cheese. 

My son enjoyed his fish and chips too.  Nice and crisp batter, decently seasoned and size is perfect.

Its been a while since our last  visit here at #tsuiwahsg and having said that, itâ€™s been over a couple of years since our last trip in Hong Kong.  We miss Hong Kong.  Oh to travel again is the next best thing! 

So we feasted on:

Lamb Chop Curry 

What I love about this dish is that they grilled the lamb chops first then smothered them with that delicious curry sauce.  This curry is very good with perfectly cooked meat, tender and not too gamey.  Best with roti or steamed rice.

Crispy Bun with Condensed Milk 

A must if you are a first timer at Tsui Wah.  This is their signature toast and we love it.  We first had this in Hong Kong and became our favorite since. 

Crispy and soft at the same time, this buttered toast bun is generously drizzled with condensed milk.  Yum!

Kagoshima-Style Braised Pork Cartilage with Tossed Instant Noodle 

My son enjoyed this bowl of goodness so much so that he finished everything except the cartilage ğŸ˜†. The meat just falls off the bone, soft, easy to eat and very tasty. 

King Prawns in Mala Soup with Mixian 

Our first time trying this noodle dish and this is now one of my favorite noodle dish here. 

This is not the mala we are more exposed to.  This bowl of goodness has a mild to medium mala heat yet you will only get that hint of spiciness and numbness a little later.  The prawns are fresh and crunchy that adds contrast to the mala soup. My only issue here is that the serving seems small.  I could probably have 2 orders of this. ğŸ˜‹ğŸ˜‹ğŸ˜‹

Amaranth with Fish Soup - We need vegetables in our daily eating life too.  Love the fish broth on this vegetable dish and the amaranth greens is the perfect vegetable for this soup.  Crunchy and hearty.

A #latepost of my birthday brunch with my best half at Bearded Bella over a week ago.  It was our first time here and overall meal was a pleasant one. 

On the table:

Salmon Pistachio Rosti $22
A generous plate of goodness.  For brunch, this meal will keep you satiated until tea time ğŸ˜ƒ. I love the citrus mint mayo and pomegranate that goes well with everything on the plate it balanced out the richness.  The salmon is perfectly done, rosti just crisp outside, soft and moist inside and I love the generous amount of pistachios. 

Epic Brekkie $25
Green tomato relish, maple bacon, harrisa chicken sausage, confit portobello, avocado, sweet potato rosti, arugula, 1 egg your way.  The perfect plate of brekkie when you are hungry.  Quite a big portion and pretty good actually.  Although I feel it is missing a sauce or gravy of some kind on the side and perhaps a light dressing on the arugula. 

Oh and they have awesome coffee too!

Carrot cake with heaps of chye poh! 

Among the stretch of HDB blocks at Yishun, youâ€™ll find @618simcarrotcake , a hawker stall serving carrot cake (Chai Tow Kway) with a unique twist. 

Carrot Cake | $3.50
The carrot cake is soft on the inside and crispy on the outside. They were generous with the amount of eggs added, which allows the carrot cake to hold together as a piece. 

Unlike the usual carrot cake, chye poh is added to the side to provide the additional flavour and juicy crunch to each bite. It is not overly salty and brings a tinge of sweetness in it. We find that the carrot cake itself was lacking flavour. But it makes sense when you eat it together with the chye poh, which struck a balance between the taste. 

The portion is huge which is good for sharing even though we ordered the small one. 

Would you prefer black or white carrot cake?

Looking for fresh, authentic sushi and sashimi? Popular Osaka Conveyor Belt Sushi Chain Chojiro could be the best option for you! 

Chojiro opened its first franchised branch in Singapore at Gochi Japan Kitchen inside Capital Square which houses five other Japanese eateries.

SEASONAL ITEMS

Kani Kyoto style steamed sushi | $20.90
Unlike your usual sushi, this sushi rice is packed into a wooden bamboo crate and topped with generous amount of kani, ikura and tamago. It is served with a fire lit at the bottom to ensure the rice is steeped with all the flavours from the toppings, making each mouthful filled with unaminess. This is definitely a highlight in the restaurant!

Kyoto Pickled Turnip Sushi | $3.90
Not the usual pickled vegetables youâ€™ve tried. The turnip is well marinated - not too sourish and gives a refreshing crunchy bite. Definitely a good appetizer to set off the meal with! 

STANDARD ITEMS

Spicy Maguro Roll | $8.20
Consists of tuna, avocado, cucumber and sushi rice with spicy sauce. 
They have a wide selection of rolls here and are really affordable. The chopped maguro is mixed with the spicy sauce and topped on the maki. They also added ebiko on top, which burst into flavours when you bite on the maki. The spicy sauce is bearable which can be easily enjoyed by all. 

Chojiro Sashimi Set (8 Kinds) | $49.90
Sea urchin, salmon roe, tuna, salmon, yellow tail, squid, botan ebi and scallop sashimi
This sashimi set is of highest freshness and quality! Something unique to be mentioned is the deep fried ebi head, the best part of the prawn where the briny juices are all concentrated there, in a crunchy form.

Crab Shrimp Creamy Gratin | $12.90
This stuffed crab shell is filled with fresh crab and shrimp meat mixed with creamy cheeses. It is perfectly grilled to give a crispy exterior and slight char. The overall taste is appealing and not too jelak. Not to be miss is the eye catching cheese pull!! ğŸ˜

Thank you @chojirosg for the kind invite and warm hospitality!
