description:
Farewell to a dear colleague and friend and we marked the occasion with a thank you dinner @imperialtreasuresg .  Being all Teochews, it was a feast full of Teochew specialities, starting with some steamed cold crab (not really my thing cos kinda troublesome ğŸ˜¬). We even had the platter including some pigâ€™s ear, you know, just as a dare to see how Teochew we are? 

Anyways braised pigâ€™s ear is something Iâ€™ve had when I was growing up (yeah thatâ€™s a long time agoâ€¦) and I remember it fondly, together with pig snout which is actually even better ğŸ˜¬. Anyways the version here is soso with more cartilage then I remember.  Another notable dish from dinner was the smoked chicken.  I didnâ€™t have much expectation as most roast chicken is just kinda meh, but the version here was tender and had a unique umami taste from the smoking process.  Quite nice, I like. 

But my favouritest dish and also more unique dish here, is the fried bee hoon like thingy.  Not sure what itâ€™s called but itâ€™s deep fried like a pancake and eat with a generous dousing of black vinegar and sugar!!! Sounds weird?  No, itâ€™s absolutely delicious imho.  Itâ€™s kinda like a yummy savoury dessert and i really love it!  I always order this whenever I see it available in a Teochew restaurant and the version here didnâ€™t disappoint! ğŸ¤¤
fullName: This Is Why Iâ€™m Fat And Broke

description: We were out of ideas and out of time, so we finally settled on a nearby bakery cafe to grab a quick brunch.  Whilst @thekazocafe_sg is not hipster cafe, their bakes turned out to be quite a surprise find!  Whilst Iâ€™m not a big fan of garlic cheese bread, the version here is pretty soft and fluffy with a generous cream filling. But what impressed me more was their range of savoury danishes.  The puff pastry was very flaky and buttery and the danishes also had generous filling.  We enjoyed both their mushroom and bacon versions.  Quite a nice find in my neighborhood, I certainly wouldnâ€™t mind buying more bakes from here in future!

ğŸš¨ Dessert Alert!

ğŸ“ Thornys, 21 Woodlands Close 
ğŸ½ MaoShanWang Mousse ($6.50)
5 â­ / 5

If you are a durian lover, this is definitely a place you have to go! And if you're not, this place might just convert you!

This MSW durian mousse has got to be one of the best durian desserts my mouth has ever had the pleasure of tasting! The mousse itself is so thick, creamy and rich, with the bittersweet MSW taste featuring so prominently! And it even comes with a huge dollop of durian at the top! I ate this thing so fast that I almost cried when I finished it! It is really THAT good!!

Also pictured:
Grass Jelly Longan ($3.50)
Mango and Pineapple Fruit Tea ($4 each)

Verdict: ğŸ¥‡ Must come again!

[Invited Tasting] ğŸ§‹Bubble Tea!

ğŸ“ MILK Singapore, 27 Arab Street
ğŸ½ Brown Sugar Milk BrÃ»lÃ©e ($6) + Chendol Royale ($6.80)
4 â­ / 5

First Muslim-owned bubble tea in Singapore! Yesterday, they had their relaunch day at their flagship store, with a brand new look and new menu! 

One of their new additions is an interactive build your own MILK wall, where you can customise your own bubble tea! First, grab a Milk or Milk Tea pail, then choose your flavours + toppings. Bring it to the counter and watch your creation turn into reality!

Milk - Strawberry, Grape, Mango
Milk Tea - Caramel, Hazelnut, Taro, Chocolate, Ovaltine
Toppings - Ice cream, Nata de coco, Grass jelly, Pearl, Jelly

~ Brown Sugar Milk BrÃ»lÃ©e 
This is a variation of the well-known brown sugar fresh milk with pearls, with a twist at the end; they add a layer of milk foam followed by a layer of sugar at the top and blowtorch it to get the nice caramelisation! I love it when you get those bits of caramelised goodness when you take a sip of the drink! Such a shame though that the plastic seal at the top hides the beautiful brown caramelisation underneath!

~ Chendol Royale 
Literally a dessert in a cup! Super authentic chendol taste, with fresh creamy coconut milk and gula melaka. It even comes with red bean and chendol to complete the drink! Although it was a tad too sweet for my liking, I would still highly recommend it! 

Verdict: ğŸ¥ˆ Can come again!
- Would definitely love to try the other signature drinks and have a go at their build your own MILK wall!

Thank you @milk.singapore for the hospitality!

#MILKyourdaybetter

â˜• Coffee alert!

ğŸ“ Starbucks, various locations
ğŸ½ Iced Smoked Butterscotch Latte, venti ($8.90)
4.2 â­ / 5

Never seen this drink before on the menu and decided to give it a shot since it sounded really intriguing! 

This drink combines espresso with steamed milk and smoked butterscotch sauce. When you take a sip, the first thing that hits you is this sweet butterscotch espresso flavour, followed by a smokey aftertaste. All the components seem to blend with each other really well, which is a pleasant surprise! The drink is rather sweet though, and so might not be everyone's cup of tea (or coffee in this case lol)! Give it a try for yourself!

Verdict: ğŸ¥‡ Sure buy again!

ğŸ¥¤ Yoghurt alert!

ğŸ“ Hey Yoghurt, various locations
ğŸ½ Avocado Yoghurt (UP $7.50)
3 â­ / 5

Hey Yoghurt is currently having a 1-for-1 promotion until 28 Feb, so of course I had to get onboard and check it out! Got 2 drinks at $7.50 i.e. each drink is $3.75 which is really value for money!!

Got the drink with 50% sugar, which was just nice and not too sweet; tastes super healthy too! The drink is super thick and smooth, which is absolutely divine! And surprisingly, it was super filling, enough to replace a whole meal for me!

Unfortunately, the avocado taste was super faint, barely perceptible if I may say so, which is such a shame considering that this is an avocado yoghurt drink. If this was a plain yoghurt drink though, it'll be at least a 4.5 â­!

Verdict: ğŸ¥ˆ Can come again!
- Heard the purple rice yoghurt is good so I'll probably try that the next time!

ğŸ¦ Frozen yoghurt alert!

ğŸ“ llao llao, various locations
ğŸ½ Large tub frozen yoghurt + 3 toppings ($7)
4.8 â­ / 5 

Seems like as these companies grow bigger, their cups grow smaller lol.

But that being said, llao llao is currently my favorite frozen yoghurt chain. Absolutely love the smooth texture and the flavours of their frozen yoghurt, just the perfect blend of sour and sweet with it not being overly sweet! And they even have premium walnuts as one of the toppings now! So obviously I got that and my 2 favourites, as always, cookie butter sauce and hazelnut chocolate sauce! You can never have too many toppings!

Verdict: ğŸ¥‡ Sure come again!

Established since 1971 at the former Mandarin Singapore, Chatterbox @chatterboxsg returns at Hilton Singapore Orchard @hiltonsingaporeorchard with a brand-new space, menu and dining experience. They are set to open next week, 14 Mar 2022.

My first visit to Chatterbox was at least 20 years ago and I came back multiple times for business lunch, dining with family and friends mainly for their Chicken Rice and Lobster Laksa. I remembered there is once Chatterbox shifted to Top of the M offers 360-degree views of the city before moving back to level 5, memorable experience. I feel that Chatterbox is not only just for business meals and visitors from overseas, but also suitable for those who are looking for a nice dining environment to catch up with friends over a meal or celebrating an occasion. If your intention is just to have a nice plate of chicken rice, finish within 10mins and go, here may not be suitable for you.

Their Mandarin Chicken Rice Set ($25.00++) is served boneless with a side of fragrant, broth-cooked jasmine rice, and warm soup, accompanied by trio of homemade signature chilli sauce, ginger puree and dark soya sauce. Aside from the Individual Mandarin Chicken Rice Set, you have options to order Half Chicken ($38.00++) and Whole Chicken ($72.00++) for sharing too.

Location: Chatterbox, Hilton Singapore Orchard, 333 Orchard Road, 05-03, Singapore 238887

Tomato & Shrimp Bisque

Sometimes you just want soup and bread. I love a good bisque. A thick and creamy soup, it started with a base made with Shrimp shells and butter giving it an intense flavour. 

Add celery, onions, garlic, thyme, bay leaves and fry, donâ€™t let it burn.

Next add water and simmer for 30mins, then sieve the stock and set aside.

In another heavy pan, add olive oil, minced garlic, thyme, onions, and celery, cook till soften. Sprinkle a little flour and stir for about a minute. This is your roux and helps thicken the soup. Add the shrimp stock, Worcestershire sauce, Cajun spices and purÃ©e in blender (you can skip this and just leave the whole soup chunky) 

I like my bisque blended but I like my tomatoes and shrimps in chunks. So Iâ€™ll add the purÃ©e soup back into a pot and add a can of chopped tomatoes, peas, cream and stir till combined. Salt & Pepper to taste. Serve with toasted bread. 

You need to get good fresh shrimps for this soup, preferably not frozen.

These beautiful Batang steaks were from @9sseafood I first air-fried them in my @ninjakitchensg Air-grill before slipping them into this fiery appetite whetting sauce. Added whatever vegetables was left in the fridge and enjoyed this fresh spicy goodness with white jasmine rice.

I grinded a simple paste from garlic, lemongrass, shallots, dried chillies and belacan and fried it in oil till fragrant.

The spawning season of rabbit fish peaks from Jan-Feb every year which overlaps the chinese new year, during which the bellies of the fish are filled with roe (eggs) and milt (semen) and are cleaner hence named æ‹œå¹´é±¼.

The rabbit fish is a common food fish found in coastal waters from the western Pacific Ocean to the eastern Indian Ocean  with the best ones believed to be from Kasu Region in Indonesia.

The rabbit fish is also known as ğ’”ğ’‘ğ’Šğ’ğ’†ğ’‡ğ’ğ’ğ’• because of its stiff, sharp dorsal and pelvic spines which are venomous (though not life threatening to humans except for a painful sting).

Piu M: Simple Home-style Japanese Italian Cooking 

7ï¸âƒ£ Uni and Bottarga Pasta 

This pasta is actually jun-sanâ€™s signature pasta which is very popular. Interestingly, jun-san cooks his pasta in a dashi broth rather than the usual water with salt which I think is a rather clever trick to give the pasta that extra flavor! He then tosses the pasta with lots of fresh sashimi-grade uni from Japan until the uni is infused into the sauce. He then tops the pasta with some bottarga, a cured fish roe, which is a really nice touch! Having tried different renditions of uni pastas from other restaurants, I have to say this version served by jun-san is my personal favorite!

Piu M: Simple Home-style Japanese Italian Cooking 

6ï¸âƒ£ Iberico Pork Seafood Stew 

This was a really interesting dish which I have not actually seen elsewhere. Jun-san manages to sear the iberico pork such that it is slightly pink and superbly tender. The pork is then stewed in a buttery seafood broth which gets its sweetness from the generous amounts of clams and cherry tomatoes. Essentially the pork absorbs some of that tasty broth which makes it a real delight!

Cheese Muffins ğŸ§€

Made this super easy and quick cheese muffin ğŸ˜Š No mixer needed just mix everything in a bowl.
They are soft, moist, yum with cheese cubes inside ğŸ§€ğŸ§€

Yield 10 muffins
Ingredients:
2 eggs
200g icing sugar
275g all purpose flour
2 tbsp milk powder
1 tsp baking powder
1/2 tsp baking soda
125g butter, melted
75g vegetable oil
90g milk
1tsp vanilla extract
100g cheddar cheese, cut into cubes
Grated cheese for topping

Directions:
1. In a bowl combine all purpose flour, milk powder, baking powder and baking soda together. Set aside. 
2. Whisk eggs and powder sugar together until fluffy about 5 minutes. 
3. Add in the dry ingredients, melted butter, vegetable oil, milk, and vanilla extract. Mix until combined. Don't overmix. 
4. Add in cheese cubes. Mix until combined
5. Portion into muffin cups. Add grated cheese on top. 
6. Bake at 170Â°C for 25 to 30 minutes

Sake Karashi Don

Checked out the new Shin Yuu Yakitori and Donburi, which is opened by the same folks behind Shin Yuu Japanese Restaurant at Greenwood Avenue that serves an ala-carte Japanese buffet â€” their latest outlet, which is located at Royal Square @ Novena (just beside Novena Square) focuses on Yakitori, Sushi, Sashimi and Donburi offerings â€” all of which being rather decently priced with the Donburi costing in the range of $12.90 to $29.90 depending on the item; the most expensive being the Uni Kaisendon.

Opted for the Sake Karashi Don, which was one of the more affordably priced items at $13.90; essentially a Donburi which features salmon sashimi slices that comes with a spicy sauce that is similar to that found of the spicy salmon in Omoteâ€™s Salmon Sanshoku Don. Here, the Don comes with wasabi and pickled ginger, and the salmon does come sprinkled with Japanese chili powder as well. Overall, the Sake Karashi Don was pretty satisfying and hit all the right spots; the salmon used was fresh with the slices of sashimi being of equal sizes â€” the spicy sauce was peppery, yet carried just enough spice to tickle the taste buds without being too fiery. The level of spiciness is pretty manageable, considering how they have only used it as a sauce here in comparison to how Omote seemingly using it as a marinade â€” should be pretty fine even for those with lower tolerance to spiciness in general. The pearly, short-grain rice came at room temperature; slightly sweetened, we also enjoyed how the rice came at a decent temperature that didnâ€™t create a stark contrast against that of the raw fish. It is also interesting to note how they had included crispy bits of fried tempura batter above the fish; really liked how that created a light crunchy texture that just made the entire bowl so interesting to have. Personally felt that the wasabi wasnâ€™t of much use considering how the salmon was already flavoured from the spicy sauce, though it does provide quite a numbing kick that tickles the taste buds.

<continuation of caption in the comments section below>

Homemade Kaya Butter Toast & Eggs

Have seen quite a fair bit about the new Babba which had opened their doors at 15-9 Jalan Riang recently â€” this is the latest venture by the same folks behind The Brewing Ground, which is located within The Yards (former site of Telok Kurau Primary School). The place sports a similar decor theme as The Brewing Ground â€” a rather clean interior decor that comes with a slight Balinese vibe with furnishing and fittings that features concrete, rattan and wooden elements. Serving up two different menus for breakfast/lunch and dinner service, Babba has rolled out its breakfast/lunch menu at the time of the writing of this post â€” dubbed â€œThe Little Babaâ€, the breakfast/lunch menu features brunch dishes with a Peranakan influence. Dinner service will be launched on a later date; named the â€œBig Babbaâ€, the dinner menu will feature â€œauthentic traditional Peranakan fareâ€ in a communal format that works for sharing across the table.

The breakfast/lunch menu is available from 8am to 4pm; split into several sections ranging from â€œbreakfastâ€ and â€œlunchâ€, to â€œsaladsâ€, â€œsides to shareâ€ and â€œdessertâ€, the Homemade Kaya Butter Toast & Eggs is from the â€œbreakfastâ€ section of the menu. Featuring elements such as brioche, house-made Kaya and French butter, the Homemade Kaya Butter Toast & Eggs is essentially a spruced up version of the local favourite breakfast â€” something that I will absolutely fall for.

<continuation of caption in the comments section below>

Crispy Cauliflower Drumlets

Visited the East Coast Road outlet of the favourite place over the weekend instead of the Guillemard Road one since we were wanting to check out another spot around Marine Parade â€” pretty much a coincidence given how the folks behind Brawn & Brains had also introduced yet another new item on the menu; the Crispy Cauliflower Drumlets.

Being part of the â€œMunchiesâ€ section of the menu, the Crispy Cauliflower Drumlets is one of those items that could be shared at the table. A great vegetarian alternative to the Crispy Karaage Chicken with Side of Sriracha Dip, the Crispy Cauliflower Drumlets is pretty much almost the same here â€” cauliflower florets with a golden brown, deep-fried batter that is sprinkled with chili powder for a subtle hint of spiciness that lingers at the taste buds. Whilst the batter for the Crispy Cauliflower Drumlets doesnâ€™t come with the bits of quinoa that gives their Crispy Karaage Chicken with Side of Sriracha Dip that extra crunch, we liked how crisp the batter was without being particularly greasy, while the cauliflower gives a soft crunch. Just like the Crispy Karaage Chicken with Side of Sriracha Dip though, they do offer a wedge of lime for a zesty touch if you do prefer it that way, though rather than to come with a sriracha dip, the Crispy Cauliflower Drumlets came with a creamy and light aioli that matches the more neutral flavours of the cauliflower here â€” a pretty thoughtful touch. Guess I now know what to order as an accompaniment to the BBFC (BB Crispy Fried Chicken) next time!

Kakuni Don

Much had been said about Itchy Bun before itâ€™s official launch â€” whilst they were supposed to have opened their doors on 22 February 2022 initially, they had finally officially done so a day after due to â€œunforeseen circumstancesâ€ as stated in their social media account. For those whom are not in the know, Itchy Bun is an establishment located at Prinsep Street (several doors away from Mama Diam) brought by the folks behind Fook Kin (also by the same people behind Roast Paradise) and also The Muttons from Class 95FM. Being more of an Izakaya-style establishment, the menu offers fry buckets (i.e. beer bites), Zensai, Rice Bowls, Itchy Buns (i.e Mantou Sliders) and sides. Beverages available include beer, sake and non-alcoholic options such as canned drinks â€” pretty much in line with the other establishments around the area. 

While we were pretty intrigued by the Itchy Buns that they have to offer initially as they seem to be the signature offerings here, but we found ourselves going for the Kakuni Don for something more substantial since we were here for lunch on a workday in office (which is pretty much a stoneâ€™s throw away from us). Ainâ€™t a fan of Foie Gras, hence steered away from the Subarashi Don which is pretty much the full works, and instead opted for the Kakuni Don. While the portions may be a bit on the smaller side for some, the Kakuni Don is actually pretty affordably priced at $8.80+. Coming with elements such as a sous-vide egg, Ebiko, Furikake, Japanese pickles, braised pork belly and seaweed, the Kakuni Don was pretty comforting and well-executed for its price â€” the braised pork belly was especially delicious having absorbed all the flavours from the braising liquid; all savoury without being too heavy-handed in flavour, while not carrying undesirable porky stench. Texturally, it was a great balance between the gelatinous fatty parts and the leaner parts; soft, tender and juicy, yet carrying a good bite for the best of both worlds.

Passionfruit Meringue Tart

Heard all about the new K. Patisserie at Onze; the same building which also houses DESEM Bakery and Sugar & Tease, as well as the ever-popular Beef Sukiyaki Don Keisuke which always sees a queue during the hours that they are open. K. Patisserie is situated within the mall, tucked in a corner not too far from where DESEM Bakery and Sugar & Tease are located. The cafe is pretty moderately-sized, with a small counter facing the patrons on the left displaying the cakes and bakes available for the day upon entry; the space being decked in a pastel pink and white colour scheme with splashes of gold for the furniture and fittings. Being a patisserie, expect a variety of cakes and bakes available here; drinks available includes specialty coffee, tea, as well as a small list of non-caffeinated options such as Chocolate and Mineral Water. 

Between the two items that we had, the one that actually set a better impression would be the Passionfruit Meringue Tart. It is the more well-executed one â€” priced at $8, it is decently sized; what we really enjoyed here is the biscuit-like tart base which crumbles quite neatly as one slices through it. The tart base also holds the passionfruit curd within pretty well; all that while the passionfruit curd remains zingy and tangy. The meringue was actually done pretty well here; fluffy and light whilst being slightly torched without being overly sweet â€” cuts through the zippy notes for a good balance of flavours. Overall, a pretty satisfying dessert for those looking for something a little sour to refresh the taste buds.

Yakiniku-GO turned 1ï¸âƒ£ on 9 Feb 2022 but they decided to celebrate their 1st anniversary today with this special ONE day promo with a 50% OFF Yakiniku-GO Set (100g + Full steak)! ğŸ˜±ğŸ˜‹

Oh boyâ€¦ how could I not be there and join in the fun? ğŸ˜‚ğŸ¤ª
I waited slightly over half an hour as there were quite a lot of people waiting to dine in given this awesome promo!
â€¨This signature Yakiniku-GO Set consists of 3 popular cuts of beef with a bowl of rice, soup and a side (a choice of kimchi, radish kimchi or mini salad).

The 3ï¸âƒ£ popular cuts of beef are:

~ Angus Ribeye Steak
~ Karubi (Beef Short Plate) 
~ Gyutan (Beef Tongue)

I loved all 3 cuts of beef.
The Angus Ribeye Steak has a great balance between lean meat and fat with beautiful marbling. 
I cooked mine to medium rare so they were still tender and juicy with that rich meaty bite and a hint of smokiness from the grill. Tasted so good! ğŸ˜‹ğŸ˜

The Karubi is fatty and has more marbling and this cut is rich in flavour and is characterised by slight sweetness.
I grilled this to medium and loved this on its own without dip for its natural flavour. So heavenly! ğŸ¤©ğŸ‘

I also liked Gyutan although it is more of an acquired taste and slightly more chewy with meaty rich taste. ğŸ¥°

A tip on how best to grill Gyutan from a pro that I learnt recently too.
As Gyutan is sliced very thinly and cooks fast, as soon as the meat starts to curl, we have to flip it over quickly. 
Best to grill one side of gyutan well while leaving the other side a bit rarer to best enjoy Gyutan. 

There are 2ï¸âƒ£ sauces provided for this set:

~ Negi Shio Tare
~ Miso Tare

The Angus Ribeye Steak and Karubi paired well with the Miso Tare.
I highly recommend to dip the Gyutan into the slight-tangy citrusy Negi Shio Tare.

I had a wonderful dinner and made even more sweet with such an awesome deal! 
Iâ€™ll definitely be back again to try out more of their meat selections. 
Their prices are really affordable too.

Happy birthday, Yakiniku-GO! ğŸ‰ğŸ¥³

Their menu for lunch and dinner everyday is different. Below is a list of dishes tried. Overall, I feel that there is a good balance of flavours across their menu for the day e.g. salty, sour, sweet and savoury.

- Fish maw and cabbage with sliced pork soup: very fresh, flavourful soup and the sliced pork was tender. Must try âœ…âœ…âœ… No MSG, I finished every drop of food. 

- Pork Chop: Seasoning is good, pork was tender âœ…âœ…

- Fish fillet with Orange Sauce: I like that it wasn't too oily or tough for the batter but some might find it soggy. You can't really see the sauce so it's not your usual sweet and sour sauce type but I can taste a hint of orange. Fish meat is tender. âœ…âœ…

- Stir fry Cabbage with Black Fungus: crunchy cabbage, lightly seasoned âœ…

I haven't done a count of how many fish ball noodle stalls (and Bak Chor Mee stalls) there are in Toa Payoh but I know Toa Payoh residents are spoilt for choice. 
ğŸœ
Song Kee Fish Ball Noodles' flagship outlet is at Yio Chu Kang. Thankfully for me, they opened a branch  at Lorong 5 Toa Payoh in March this year.
ğŸœ
Their Hee Keow (fish dumpling) is seriously shiok - handmade, with a generous amount of fish meat. The texture was not too gooey.  The noodles were just a touch on the soggy side (those who like their noodles eggy will enjoy this). Chilli packed a punch. Was served by the elder brother today. Super friendly. Featured here is the $5.00 bowl that comes with 2 fishballs and 1 hee keow.
ğŸœ
There wasn't a crowd at 8am and the cool morning breeze made for a perfect breakfast.
ğŸœ
Open daily. 7am to 10pm
ğŸœ
#foodaddict #foodie #sgfoodie #sgeats #hawkersg #hawkercultre #singaporehawker #foodspotting #breakfast #fishballnoodles #songkeefishballnoodle #foodiesg #streeteats #igfoodies

Finally made it here. Ordered their signature bowl which had hee keow, fish balls and minced pork.  The owners  May & Jeevan were not there but 2 friendly Auntie's were. Auntie  asked me specifically if I wanted chilli and vinegar, and when I said no chilli just vinegar she "white". Loved her attention to detail
ğŸœ
Noodles were nice and springy and flavour was not too heavy.  Lots of pork lard but overall the dish didn't feel oily. Noodles were generous. Hee Keow chewy (just 1 piece, if you want more best to order a bowl of hee keow soup), fish balls (not handmade) were good. 
ğŸœ
Hee Keow available for takeaway (frozen)

description:
Continuing on with the tour of Pek Kio Market & Food Centre
ğŸ¥•
Good Spice Carrot Cake always sees a long queue at weekends. Head there early (they start at 6am). The carrot "cake" is soft  and wobbly and is not fried flat or crispy like  some other stalls.  I only had stomach space for the white version. Old school, comforting, shiok! Chilli good too.
ğŸ¥•
Trivia : the "carrot" isn't the carrot as we know it. It is white radish. It is shredded, mixed with rice flour and steamed. The "cake" is then ready to be used to make Carrot Cake aka known locally as Chye Tow Kway. Estee in Sweden has a clear video on how to make the "cake"  on her You Tube Channel (no I don't know her, just sharing)
ğŸ¥•
Closed Tuesdays & Wednesdays
Opens at 6am
$2.00 / $3.00
ğŸ¥•
#foodie #sgfoodie #hawkerculture #hawkersg #pekkiomarket #singaporefoodie #breakfast #eatsg #sgeats #food #heritagefood #streetfood #carrotcake #mysingapore #shiok #sgfoodies

Pek Kio Market is home to several great hawker stalls including 2 stalls selling Prawn Noodles.  The more popular one would be Wah Kee Big Prawn Noodle located in the centre block of the hawker centre.  However if one walks to the last row of hawker stalls you will find, at the corner, a queue at Lai Hiang.  Helmed by a friendly lady I got my bowl of noodles after a 10 minute wait in the queue.  Go early because the queue seems to get longer as the morning progresses (this was a thursday). A nice bowl of noodles for $3.00. The chilli was shiok and soup was not too rich. A nice balance of pork and Prawn broth.
ğŸ¦
I suppose I should have braved Wah Kee (even though there was no queue) but I was pretty full. Next week perhaps. Lai Hiang is closed on tuesdays and fridays.
ğŸ¦

Savory bite size snacks - Golden Puffy Yam cake is my favourite out of X.O Carrot Cake and Pumpkin Abacus Seed! As a taro fan, I could taste the taro in it!

ğŸ”¸Simply Nasi Goreng
Turmeric Fried Rice with smoky beancurd, pickled vegetables, sunny-side up and crispy crackers. Love how the chilli goes well  with the Nasi!

ğŸ”¸Beetroot Churros Rojak
Elemenâ€™s exemplary effort to use beetroot churros in replacement of youtiao! I love this refreshing appetiser with its rich mix of vegetables and fruits.

Visited @indulgence_by_roxey, a newly opened cafe in Telok Kurau a couple of weeks back. The cafe has a really nice interior (especially on the 2nd floor), and the food is pretty good overall too! Hereâ€™s what we had:
â€¢
~Blue Surf Pizza: This was our first time seeing blue pizza, and we werenâ€™t sure what to expect! To our pleasant surprise, this was delicious! Itâ€™s a pizza naturally coloured with butterfly pea flower, topped with shrimps, honey baked ham, pineapple and mozzarella. The dough had a nice bite to it, and the toppings went harmoniously well together!
â€¢
~Chilli Crab Shakshuka: This was really yummy! The shakshuka itself is already pretty indulgent, but the eggs added even more richness to the dish! And it went so well with the buttered toast too!
â€¢
~Azzuro Aglio Olio: Similar to the pizza, it was our first time seeing blue pasta too! This is a handmade butterfly pea flower pappardelle pasta served with shrimps, garlic and chilli flakes. â€¢
~The Orient: This is a platter that includes a combination of pan-fried Asian style dumplings with shrimp & pork filling, and Braised Korean pork belly (bossam) & Indonesian style roasted pork belly served with kimchi and achar. Itâ€™s surprisingly cheap as compared to the usual restaurant BKT and quality isnâ€™t compromised!

With all the hype surrounding @yatkayanâ€™s traditional desserts, we definitely had to make our way down to see what all the fuss is about!

Smooth, thick and flavorful with bits of yam and lots of gingko nuts â€“ taste and texture wise, it really reminded us of the ones served at weddings, which we definitely love. We also thoroughly enjoyed their Ice Jelly with Soursop and Passionfruit. The tanginess of this bowl served as a refreshing contrast. This dessert may be overshadowed by all the hot options on the menu, but we highly recommend it as well!

Do you fancy a classic good ol'  type of #wantonmee ? Unlike Klang Valley ones that are often heavily flavored with pork lard oil, dark soy sauce and light soy sauce, this springy noodles at #khengpincafe is lightly salted and tossed with chicken broth for a wetter, smoother texture. The wanton noodles are then paired up with #bqqpork #charsiu , shredded chicken, green leaves and succulent, juicy #wanton dumplings . Just taking a bite stirred fond memories of school days where my friends and I will ride our bikes to a coffee shop for a simple but satisfying plate of wanton mee ğŸ˜Š

Braved the CNY jam and drove up to Batu Feringghi bumper to bumper for 50 mins to a small little hut serving delectable #hainanesefood and yes the place is small. It can only cater to about 8 tables max. So do book ahead if you plan on going.

Wanted to order the popular chicken pot pie but it was too huge a portion for us. So had their #hainanesechickenchop , hailam noodles and sizzling #porkchop instead though the pork chop didn't turn out how I was expecting it to be ğŸ˜… It was more of stir-fried pork slices served on a hot plate. The homemade #springrolls were my favorite amongst the food ordered and they are not your average size rolls. I will be completely full from eating a plate of this ğŸ˜

This #prawnfritters is my no. 1 #musteat when I visit #Penang . It's perfectly deep fried to just the right crunch that feels light to the bite and is filled with big prawns. Their #lohbak or #ngohiang is also very good. Thank goodness they reopened the day I was leaving Penang. If not my trip would have felt lacking this awesome eat.

Pitt Street #kuayteowthng but location is  actually at Carnavon Street #Penang as they have relocated from their original location.

Their specialty here is eel meat #fishball  but not too worry if you don't eat eel meat as you can't really taste it in the fishball. The soup has a strong 3-in-1 broth taste as it is boiled with chicken bones, pork bones and duck bones ğŸ˜‹

Uniquely, the flat piece of meat is actually made of minced pork and is not fish paste nor fish cake.

McDonald's 

Hopped on the bandwagon to try the special BTS meal ($8.90). If you like McNuggets, it definitely doesn't disappoint. For the sauces, i think the sweet chilli dip was the better one, as it was a slightly sweeter version of the old McDonalds sweet chilli sauce. The Cajun dip really wasn't a Cajun dip, more like a spicy mustard-mayo like dip that caused a stinging sensation in the nose. Personally, i prefer the new honey dip that Mcdonalds offers compared to these two.

Smitten Ice Cream Bar

Throwback to when we could still go out and eat, Smitten is a quaint little neighbourhood dessert spot with delicious ice cream.

Signature Waffle ($5.20) with Ice Cream (from $4.20 per scoop) - We got the Artisan Chocolate, Speculoos, and Premium Pistachio flavours. The ice cream was as pleasing to the tastebuds as they were to the eye, and the texture was smooth and rich. The waffles were nice and fluffy on the inside while maintaining a crisp exterior. However, I would skip the chocolate sauce, the quality of that wasn't great. Will definitely go back to try the other creative flavours, such as Atas Paddle Pop!

#sgdessert #sgicecream  #sgwaffles

Mott 32

The ambience of Mott 32 is really fancy and the menu certainly matches that. The quality of the food here is unparalleled.

South Australian Scallop, Prawn, Hot & Sour Shanghainese Soup Dumplings ($10) - The colour of the dumplings already sets the tone for the vibrant burst of flavours you can expect from these dumplings. It's tangier than the classic pork XLBs we know and love, similar to hot & sour soup.

Barbecue Pluma Iberico Pork, Yellow Mountain Honey ($48) - When I saw the price for this dish, I was taken aback. Who pays $48 for char siew? But to the sceptics let me assure you that it is the best char siew you will ever eat in your life. The honey gently caramelised the exterior of each piece, while leaving the interior perfectly melt-in-your-mouth tender. Definitely a must-order at Mott 32!

Cold Free-Range Chicken, Szechuan Peppercorns, Chilli Sauce ($26) - The sauce was numbingly-delicious as the szechuan peppercorns gave it a mala-like flavour. The chicken was extremely tender and went perfectly with the sauce. It was like chicken rice chicken, but elevated to a whole new level with that fantastic sauce. I recommend eating it with steamed rice to absorb all the sauce you can!

#mott32sg #charsiewsg #xlb #malachicken #mott32 #sgfood #sgfoodies #charsiew #xiaolongbao

Menbaka Fire Ramen

The wait was really long and the service wasn't great, but it's good to check it out if you want to experience the theatrical, burn your eyebrows off show.

Kara Miso Fire Ramen ($19.90) - I ordered the spicy ramen, which tasted like a pretty standard spicy ramen, with an almost mala-like flavour. The ramen comes with spring onion, black fungus, corn, and one piece of chashu, which was quite chewy and tasteless. I added the egg as well ($3) which was delicious.

Crispy Karaage Salad ($13.90) - Nothing to rave about, just some pretty mediocre veggies with sesame dressing. The karaage was crispy, but not hot.

Pacific Rim is a 2013 American science fiction monster film directed by Guillermo del Toro, starring Charlie Hunnam, Idris Elba, Rinko Kikuchi, Charlie Day, Robert Kazinsky, Max Martini, and Ron Perlman, and the first film in the Pacific Rim franchise. 

The screenplay was written by Travis Beacham and del Toro from a story by Beacham. The film is set in the future, when Earth is at war with the Kaiju, colossal sea monsters which have emerged from an interdimensional portal on the bottom of the Pacific Ocean. 

To combat the monsters, humanity unites to create the Jaegers, gigantic humanoid mechas, each controlled by two co-pilots whose minds are joined by a mental link. 

Focusing on the war's later days, the story follows Raleigh Becket, a washed-up Jaeger pilot called out of retirement and teamed with rookie pilot Mako Mori as part of a last-ditch effort to defeat the Kaiju.

#pacificrim #kaiju #jaeger #movie #thehistoryprofessorwhotravels #pacificocean

By the 6th century in the Chao Phraya River Valley, Mon peoples had coalesced to create the Dvaravati kingdoms. 

In the north, Haripunjaya (Lamphun) emerged as a rival power to the Dvaravati. By the 8th century the Mon had pushed north to create city states, in Fa Daet (modern Kalasin, northeastern Thailand), Sri Gotapura (Sikhottabong) near modern Tha Khek, Laos, Muang Sua (Luang Prabang), and Chantaburi (Vientiane). 

In the 8th century CE, Sri Gotapura (Sikhottabong) was the strongest of these early city states, and controlled trade throughout the middle Mekong region. 

The city states were loosely bound politically, but were culturally similar and introduced Therevada Buddhism from Sri Lankan missionaries throughout the region.

#laos #vietiane #southeastasia #history #thehistoryprofessorwhotravels #laosairlines #nightphotography

Douglas MacArthur (26 January 1880 â€“ 5 April 1964) was an American military leader who served as General of the Army for the United States, as well as a Field Marshal to the Philippine Army. 

He was Chief of Staff of the United States Army during the 1930s and he played a prominent role in the Pacific theater during World War II. 

Macarthur received the Medal of Honor for his service in the Philippines campaign. 

This made him and his father Arthur MacArthur Jr. the first father and son to be awarded the medal. 

He was one of only five to rise to the rank of General of the Army in the U.S. Army, and the only one conferred the rank of field marshal in the Philippine Army.

#douglasmacarthur #worldwar2 #koreanwar #general #unitedstates #thehistoryprofessorwhotravels #fieldmarshal #history

ğŸ”¸Potato PancakeğŸ”¸

Dear Parents, I hope you are doing well today. It's the first day of the 875 times we are having home based learning and I'm not sure why I still decided to cook today. The chaos have settled a little by afternoon. Since there are some leftover potatoes from days before, the kids had potato pancake for lunch, a dish inspired by the Polish placki. Some grilled and shredded salmon were added, making each piece of the pancake rather filling. Shall keep this post short and sweet. Gearing up for the next 9 days!

#sgmotherhood #hbl
#homebasedlearning #sgmummies #sgkids #sgschools #homemade #foodforkids #potatorecipe #toddlerfoodideas #sgfood #kidsmealideas #kidslunch #toddlerfood #homecooked

ğŸ”¸Kids Favourite Sweet & Sour Dish ğŸ”¸
é…¸ç”œå’•å’¾è‚‰é…ç±³é¥­åƒ, å¤ªå¼€èƒƒäº†ï¼

This must be one of the most popular dishes in every Chinese restaurant. I don't know any kids who don't enjoy the sweet and sour pork. Certainly, my all time favourite childhood dish and even now, i stilll love it! What's more, the beta carotene and Vitamin C in bell peppers are well absorbed in the presence of iron and fat found in meat. Very riped pineapple was used in this recipe to enhance the natural sweetness. Also, apple cider vinegar is a good substitute if there's no vinegar for Chinese cooking, just like in my kitchen :) Here's a recipe I've simplified and tested which has turned out well. Hope you try out too. ğŸ˜‰

Ingredients :

Sliced Fish/ Sliced Pork Shoulder
Onion (preferably red but I used the white as i had that) 
Tricolour Bell Peppers
Tomato, Red and Ripe 
Sliced Pineapple
Corn Starch 
Plain Flour
Cooking Oil

Sauce 
Tomato Sauce (6 tbsp) 
Brown sugar (2.5 tbsp) 
Apple Cider Vinegar (2 tbsp) 
Soy sauce (1 teaspoon) 
Cornstarch (1 teaspoon)
Water (3 tbsp) 
*mix well 

Method :

1. Pat dry the fish/pork. Slice and coat with plain flour throughly. Then coat with cornstarch. Press each piece with cornstarch firmly before frying. 
2. When the oil is hot enough, fry the sliced fish/pork til golden brown.  Set aside. 

* For healthier alternative method, you can airfry. 

 3. Using the same wok, after removing the oil, leave a little to stir fry the vegetables til slightly soften. Dont overcook. Remove the vegetables and set aside. 
4. Then, pour in the sauce and cook for a minute  or until the sauce starts to thicken. 
5. Add in vegetables and the fried meat. 
6. Coat well with the sauce and serve.

SANKRANTI
Jewel, Changi
Indian Cuisine from down south, the state of Andhra Pradesh. Usually spicy, this cuisine is full & bursting with southern flavours.  Vegetarian hubby loooves it for the spice, I like the flavours, and always request for lesser spice ğŸ˜„
We ordered cheese stuffed mushroom kebab and masala papad for starters. The main course was gongura paneer. Gongura is a reddish leavy vegetable popular in central, western and some southern places in India. It has a tangy flavour and is different from most other greens. Also had Lemon Carrot Rasam, southern version of soup, usually made for good digestion. Kadai Veg (mixed vegetable). The rotis were Kasthuri paratha & Lacha (layered) paratha
If you have taste for southern Indian food, you will love this.
$82 for 2 pax

The Royal Albatross
Sentosa

23 years of 23rd October!! Married the guy when I was just 24 years old. A marriage full of ups and downs, but never a dull or boring moment ğŸ˜‚ğŸ˜‚ Good or bad times, there was always excitement!!
So he booked us a table onboard the Royal Albatross. The dinner cruise, with a three course meal, was my anniversary surprise!
Dinner under the moonlight. The sound of the ocean. 
Singapore coastline lit up with bright lights in the distance. 
We are not the romantic type, so we spoke about work, our children, family ... but it was fun & joy throughout.
The meal was good. 
The service was great.
The staff was very pleasant & friendly.
We started with a mini focaccia & brioche bun, with a fizzy drink. Complimentary!
Appetizer was scallops, main course was chicken, and dessert was cake with ice-cream. The man had pasta because he is vegetarian. 
Its a set menu & all pre-ordered.
But they do have a bar, and you can order drinks if you like.
Expensive, as it works out to about $250 per person (minimum), depending on what package you take.
But this is not about the food, its about the experience. So if you can afford it, its all worth it.

Today Iâ€™d like to share my simple, fast, and yet delicious recipe. Thatâ€™s Teriyaki Rice Bowl with Yumeat Plant-based Luncheon meat. Although itâ€™s plant-based luncheon meat by @yumeat.malaysia, it tastes scrumptious ğŸ˜‹ 

Difficulty: Super Easy
Time: 15 mins
Number of servings: 2

Ingredients:
* Yumeat Plant-based Luncheon meat
* 200g (7oz) Shimeji mushrooms
* Teriyaki Sauce - 2tbsp
* Lettuce leaves
* 2 bowls rice
* 2 half-boiled eggs 

Directions:
1. Dice Yumeat Plant-based Luncheon meat. Remove the stem of Shimeji mushrooms then cut into bite-size pieces.
2. Heat cooking oil in a frying pan, cook diced Yumeat Plant-based Luncheon meat until nicely browned.
3. Cook Shimeji mushrooms until coated with oil. Cook together with Yumeat Plant-based Luncheon meat Season and add Teriyaki sauce.
4. Serve rice in a bowl, place lettuce leaves, put Teriyaki Yumeat Plant-based Luncheon meat, and garnish with boiled eggs.
